# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-humane-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A catastrophic magnitude 7.0 Mw earthquake struck Haiti at 16:53 local time (21:53 UTC) on Tuesday, 12 January 2010.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The epicenter was near the town of Léogâne, Ouest department, approximately 25 kilometres (16 mi) west of Port-au-Prince, Haiti's capital.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] By 24 January, at least 52 aftershocks measuring 4.5 or greater had been recorded.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] An estimated three million people were affected by the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Death toll estimates range from 100,000 to about 160,000; the Haitian government estimated the death toll to range from 220,000 to 316,000, although these figures are a matter of some dispute.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The earthquake is the deadliest natural disaster of the 21st century for a single country.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The government of Haiti estimated that 250,000 residences and 30,000 commercial buildings had collapsed or were severely damaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Haiti's history of national debt, prejudicial trade policies by other countries, and foreign intervention into national affairs contributed to the existing poverty and poor housing conditions that increased the death toll from the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The earthquake caused major damage in Port-au-Prince, Jacmel and other cities in the region.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Notable landmark buildings were significantly damaged or destroyed, including the Presidential Palace, the National Assembly building, the Port-au-Prince Cathedral, and the main jail.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Among those killed were Archbishop of Port-au-Prince Joseph Serge Miot and opposition leader Micha Gaillard.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The headquarters of the United Nations Stabilization Mission in Haiti (MINUSTAH), located in the capital, collapsed, killing many, including the mission's chief, Hédi Annabi.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Many countries responded to appeals for humanitarian aid, pledging funds and dispatching rescue and medical teams, engineers and support personnel.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The most-watched telethon in history aired on 22 January, called *Hope for Haiti Now*, raising US$58 million by the next day.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Port-au-Prince's morgues were overwhelmed with tens of thousands of bodies.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] As rescues tailed off, supplies, medical care and sanitation became priorities.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Delays in aid distribution led to angry appeals from aid workers and survivors, and looting and sporadic violence were observed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 22 January, the United Nations noted that the emergency phase of the relief operation was drawing to a close, and on the following day, the Haitian government officially called off the search for survivors.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The island of Hispaniola, shared by Haiti and the Dominican Republic, is seismically active and has a history of destructive earthquakes.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] During Haiti's time as a French colony, earthquakes were recorded by French historian Moreau de Saint-Méry (1750–1819).
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] He described damage done by an earthquake in 1751, writing that "only one masonry building had not collapsed" in Port-au-Prince; he also wrote that the "whole city collapsed" in the 1770 Port-au-Prince earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Cap-Haïtien, other towns in the north of Haiti and the Dominican Republic, and the Sans-Souci Palace were destroyed during an earthquake on 7 May 1842.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A magnitude 8.0 earthquake struck the Dominican Republic and shook Haiti on 4 August 1946, producing a tsunami that killed 1,790 people and injured many others.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Haiti is the poorest country in the Western Hemisphere and is ranked 149th of 182 countries on the Human Development Index.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Australian government's travel advisory site had previously expressed concerns that Haitian emergency services would be unable to cope in the event of a major disaster, and the country is considered "economically vulnerable" by the Food and Agriculture Organization.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Haiti has experienced a number of natural disasters.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In addition to earthquakes, it has been struck frequently by tropical cyclones, which have caused flooding and widespread damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The most recent cyclones to hit the island before the earthquake were Tropical Storm Fay and hurricanes Gustav, Hanna and Ike, all in the summer of 2008, causing nearly 800 deaths.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The magnitude 7.0 Mw earthquake occurred inland, on 12 January 2010 at 16:53 (UTC−05:00), approximately 25 km (16 mi) WSW from Port-au-Prince at a depth of 13 km (8.1 mi) on blind thrust faults associated with the Enriquillo-Plantain Garden fault system and lasted less than 30 seconds.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] There is no evidence of surface rupture; based on seismological, geological and ground deformation data, it is also thought that the earthquake did not involve significant lateral slip on the main Enriquillo fault.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Strong shaking associated with intensity IX on the Modified Mercalli scale (MM) was recorded in Port-au-Prince and its suburbs.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] It was also felt in several surrounding countries and regions, including Cuba (MM III in Guantánamo), Jamaica (MM II in Kingston), Venezuela (MM II in Caracas), Puerto Rico (MM II–III in San Juan), and the bordering Dominican Republic (MM III in Santo Domingo).
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Geological Survey, approximately 3.5 million people lived in the area that experienced shaking intensity of MM VII to X, a range that can cause moderate to very heavy damage even to earthquake-resistant structures.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Shaking damage was more severe than for other quakes of similar magnitude due to the quake's shallow depth.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The quake occurred in the vicinity of the northern boundary where the Caribbean tectonic plate shifts eastwards by about 20 mm (0.79 in) per year in relation to the North American plate.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The rupture was roughly 65 km (40 mi) long with mean slip of 1.8 metres (5 ft 11 in).
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Preliminary analysis of the slip distribution found amplitudes of up to about 4 m (13 ft) using ground motion records from all over the world.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Wiggins-Grandison noted that the Enriquillo-Plantain Garden fault zone could be at the end of its seismic cycle and concluded that a worst-case forecast would involve a 7.2 Mw earthquake, similar in size to the 1692 Jamaica earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] An article published in Haiti's *Le Matin* newspaper in September 2008 cited comments by geologist Patrick Charles to the effect that there was a high risk of major seismic activity in Port-au-Prince.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Geological Survey recorded eight aftershocks in the two hours after the main earthquake, with magnitudes between 4.3 and 5.9.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Within the first nine hours, 32 aftershocks of magnitude 4.2 or greater were recorded, 12 of which measured magnitude 5.0 or greater; in addition, on 24 January, the US Geological Survey reported that there had been 52 aftershocks measuring 4.5 or greater since the main quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 20 January, at 06:03 local time (11:03 UTC), the strongest aftershock since the earthquake, measuring magnitude 5.9 Mw, struck Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] USGS reported its epicenter was about 56 km (35 mi) WSW of Port-au-Prince, which would place it almost exactly under the coastal town of Petit-Goâve.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A UN representative reported that the aftershock collapsed seven buildings in the town.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] According to staff of the International Committee of the Red Cross, which had reached Petit-Goâve for the first time the day before the aftershock, the town was estimated to have lost 15% of its buildings, and was suffering the same shortages of supplies and medical care as the capital.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Workers from the charity Save the Children reported hearing "already weakened structures collapsing" in Port-au-Prince, but most sources reported no further significant damage to infrastructure in the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Further casualties are thought to have been minimal since people had been sleeping in the open.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami warning immediately after the initial quake, but quickly cancelled it.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Nearly two weeks later it was reported that the beach of the small fishing town of Petit Paradis was hit by a localised tsunami shortly after the earthquake, probably as a result of an underwater landslide, and this was later confirmed by researchers.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] At least three people were swept out to sea by the wave and were reported dead.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Witnesses told reporters that the sea first retreated and a "very big wave" followed rapidly, crashing ashore and sweeping boats and debris into the ocean.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The tsunami reached heights up to 3 m (9.8 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The quake affected the three Médecins Sans Frontières (Doctors Without Borders) medical facilities around Port-au-Prince, causing one to collapse completely.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A hospital in Pétion-Ville, a wealthy suburb of Port-au-Prince, also collapsed, as did the St.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Michel District Hospital in the southern town of Jacmel, which was the largest referral hospital in south-east Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The quake seriously damaged the control tower at Toussaint L'Ouverture International Airport.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Damage to the Port-au-Prince seaport rendered the harbor unusable for immediate rescue operations; its container crane subsided severely at an angle because of weak foundations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Gonaïves seaport in northern Haiti remained operational.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Roads were blocked with road debris or the surfaces broken.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The main road linking Port-au-Prince with Jacmel remained blocked ten days after the earthquake, hampering delivery of aid to Jacmel.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] When asked why the road had not been opened, Hazem el-Zein, head of the south-east division of the UN World Food Programme said that "We ask the same questions to the people in charge...They promise rapid response.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] To be honest, I don't know why it hasn't been done.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] There was considerable damage to communications infrastructure.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The public telephone system was not available, and two of Haiti's largest cellular telephone providers, Digicel and Comcel Haiti, both reported that their services had been affected by the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Fibre-optic connectivity was also disrupted.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] According to Reporters Sans Frontières (RSF), Radio Lumière, which broadcasts out of Port-au-Prince and reaches 90% of Haiti, was initially knocked off the air, but it was able to resume broadcasting across most of its network within a week.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] According to RSF, some 20 of about 50 stations that were active in the capital region before the earthquake were back on air a week after the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In February 2010, Prime Minister Jean-Max Bellerive estimated that 250,000 residences and 30,000 commercial buildings were severely damaged and needed to be demolished.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The deputy mayor of Léogâne reported that 90% of the town's buildings had been destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Many government and public buildings were damaged or destroyed including the Palace of Justice, the National Assembly, the Supreme Court and Port-au-Prince Cathedral.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The National Palace was severely damaged, though President René Préval and his wife Elisabeth Delatour Préval escaped without injury.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Prison Civile de Port-au-Prince was also destroyed, allowing around 4,000 inmates to escape.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Minister of Education Joel Jean-Pierre stated that the education system had "totally collapsed".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] About half the nation's schools and the three main universities in Port-au-Prince were affected.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] More than 1,300 schools and 50 health care facilities were destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The earthquake also destroyed a nursing school in the capital and severely damaged the country's primary midwifery school.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Haitian art world suffered great losses; artworks were destroyed, and museums and art galleries were extensively damaged, among them Port-au-Prince's main art museum, Centre d'Art school, College Saint Pierre and Holy Trinity Cathedral.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The headquarters of the United Nations Stabilization Mission in Haiti (MINUSTAH) at Christopher Hotel and offices of the World Bank were destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The building housing the offices of Citibank in Port-au-Prince collapsed, killing five employees.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The clothing industry, which accounts for two-thirds of Haiti's exports, reported structural damage at manufacturing facilities.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The quake created a landslide dam on the Rivière de Grand Goâve.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] As of February 2010 the water level was low, but engineer Yves Gattereau believed the dam could collapse during the rainy season, which would flood Grand-Goâve 12 km (7.5 mi) downstream.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In the nights following the earthquake, many people in Haiti slept in the streets, on pavements, in their cars, or in makeshift shanty towns either because their houses had been destroyed, or they feared standing structures would not withstand aftershocks.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Construction standards are low in Haiti; the country has no building codes.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Engineers have stated that it is unlikely many buildings would have stood through any kind of disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Structures are often raised wherever they can fit; some buildings were built on slopes with insufficient foundations or steel supports.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A representative of Catholic Relief Services has estimated that about two million Haitians lived as squatters on land they did not own.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The country also suffered from shortages of fuel and potable water even before the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Some high-ranking government workers lost family members, or had to tend to wounded relatives.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Although the president and his remaining cabinet met with UN planners each day, there remained confusion as to who was in charge and no single group had organized relief efforts as of 16 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The government handed over control of the airport to the United States to hasten and ease flight operations, which had been hampered by the damage to the air traffic control tower.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Almost immediately Port-au-Prince's morgue facilities were overwhelmed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] By 14 January, a thousand bodies had been placed on the streets and pavements.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Government crews collected thousands more by truck, burying them in mass graves.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In the heat and humidity, corpses buried in rubble began to decompose and smell.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Mati Goldstein, head of the Israeli ZAKA International Rescue Unit delegation to Haiti, described the situation as "Shabbat from hell.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Everywhere, the acrid smell of bodies hangs in the air.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] It's just like the stories we are told of the Holocaust – thousands of bodies everywhere.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] You have to understand that the situation is true madness, and the more time passes, there are more and more bodies, in numbers that cannot be grasped.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Mayor Jean-Yves Jason said that officials argued for hours about what to do with the volume of corpses.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The government buried many in mass graves, some above-ground tombs were forced open so bodies could be stacked inside, and others were burned.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Mass graves were dug in a large field outside the settlement of Titanyen, north of the capital; tens of thousands of bodies were reported as having been brought to the site by dump truck and buried in trenches dug by earth movers.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Max Beauvoir, a Vodou priest, protested the lack of dignity in mass burials, stating, "... it is not in our culture to bury people in such a fashion, it is desecration".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Towns in the eastern Dominican Republic began preparing for tens of thousands of refugees, and by 16 January hospitals close to the border had been filled to capacity with Haitians.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Some began reporting having expended stocks of critical medical supplies such as antibiotics by 17 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The border was reinforced by Dominican soldiers, and the government of the Dominican Republic asserted that all Haitians who crossed the border for medical assistance would be allowed to stay only temporarily.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A local governor stated, "We have a great desire and we will do everything humanly possible to help Haitian families.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] But we have our limitations with respect to food and medicine.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Slow distribution of resources in the days after the earthquake resulted in sporadic violence, with looting reported.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] There were also accounts of looters wounded or killed by vigilantes and neighbourhoods that had constructed their own roadblock barricades.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Dr Evan Lyon of Partners in Health, working at the General Hospital in Port-au-Prince, claimed that misinformation and overblown reports of violence had hampered the delivery of aid and medical services.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Former US president Bill Clinton acknowledged the problems and said Americans should "not be deterred from supporting the relief effort" by upsetting scenes such as those of looting.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Keen, deputy commander of US Southern Command, however, announced that despite the stories of looting and violence, there was less violent crime in Port-au-Prince after the earthquake than before.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In many neighbourhoods, singing could be heard through the night and groups of men coordinated to act as security as groups of women attempted to take care of food and hygiene necessities.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] During the days following the earthquake, hundreds were seen marching through the streets in peaceful processions, singing and clapping.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The earthquake caused an urgent need for outside rescuers to communicate with Haitians whose main or only language is Haitian Creole.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] As a result, a mobile translation program to translate between English and Haitian Creole had to be written quickly.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The generation of waste from relief operations was referred to as a "second disaster".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The United States military reported that millions of water bottles and styrofoam food packages were distributed although there was no operational waste management system.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Over 700,000 plastic tarpaulins and 100,000 tents were required for emergency shelters.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The increase in plastic waste, combined with poor disposal practices, resulted in open drainage channels being blocked, increasing the risk of disease.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The earthquake struck in the most populated area of the country.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies estimated that as many as 3 million people had been affected by the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In mid February 2010, the Haitian government reported the death toll to have reached 230,000.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A report from the Inter-American Development Bank in February 2010 gave a range of 200,000 to 250,000 dead, stating that it was "the most destructive event a country has ever experienced when measured in terms of the number of people killed as a share of the country's population".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] However, an investigation by Radio Netherlands has questioned the official death toll, reporting an estimate of 92,000 deaths as being a more realistic figure.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On the first anniversary of the earthquake, 12 January 2011, Haitian Prime Minister Jean-Max Bellerive said the death toll from the quake was more than 316,000, raising the figures from previous estimates.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Also killed were a number of well-known Haitian musicians and sports figures, including thirty members of the Fédération Haïtienne de Football.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] At least 85 United Nations personnel working with MINUSTAH were killed, among them the Mission Chief, Hédi Annabi, his deputy, Luiz Carlos da Costa, and police commissioner Douglas Coates.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Around 200 guests were killed in the collapse of the Hôtel Montana in Port-au-Prince.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 31 May 2011, an unreleased draft report based on a survey commissioned by the US Agency for International Development (USAID) challenged the Haiti earthquake death toll and several damage estimates.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The unpublished report put the death toll between 46,000 and 85,000 and put the number of displaced persons at 895,000, of which only 375,000 remained in temporary shelters.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The unreleased report, which compiled its figures from a door-to-door survey, was done by a Washington consulting firm, LTL Strategies.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A US State Department spokesperson said the report had inconsistencies and would not be released until they were resolved.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] As of January 2012, USAID has not released the report and states on its website that 1.5 million people were displaced, of which 550,000 remain without permanent shelter.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The most reliable academic estimate of the number of earthquake casualties in Haiti (over 95% were in the immediate Port-au-Prince area) "within six weeks of the earthquake" appears to be the 160,000 estimate in a 2010 University of Michigan study.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A 2013 preprint study placed the death toll at around 137,000.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Appeals for humanitarian aid were issued by many aid organizations, the United Nations and president René Préval.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Raymond Joseph, Haiti's ambassador to the United States, and his nephew, singer Wyclef Jean, who was called upon by Préval to become a "roving ambassador" for Haiti, also pleaded for aid and donations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Images and testimonials circulating after the earthquake across the internet and through social media helped to intensify the reaction of global engagement.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Many countries responded to the appeals and launched fund-raising efforts, as well as sending search and rescue teams.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The neighbouring Dominican Republic was the first country to give aid to Haiti, sending water, food and heavy-lifting machinery.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Dominican website FlyDominicanRepublic.com made available to the internet, daily updates on airport information and news from the operations center on the Dominican side.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Dominican emergency team assisted more than 2,000 injured people, while the Dominican Institute of Telecommunications (Indotel) helped with the restoration of some telephone services.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Dominican Red Cross coordinated early medical relief in conjunction with the International Red Cross.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The government sent eight mobile medical units along with 36 doctors including orthopaedic specialists, traumatologists, anaesthetists, and surgeons.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In addition, 39 trucks carrying canned food were dispatched, along with 10 mobile kitchens and 110 cooks capable of producing 100,000 meals per day.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Other nations from farther afield also sent personnel, medicines, materiel, and other aid to Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The first team to arrive in Port-au-Prince was ICE-SAR from Iceland, landing within 24 hours of the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A 50-member Chinese team arrived early Thursday morning.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A rescue team sent by the Israel Defense Forces' Home Front Command established a field hospital near the United Nations building in Port-au-Prince with specialised facilities to treat children, the elderly, and women in labor.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] It was set up in eight hours and began operations on the evening of 16 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A Korean International Disaster Relief Team of 40 rescuers, medical doctors, nurses and two police dogs was deployed to epicenters to assist mitigation efforts of Haitian Government.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The American Red Cross announced on 13 January that it had run out of supplies in Haiti and appealed for public donations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Giving Children Hope worked to get much-needed medicines and supplies on the ground.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Partners in Health (PIH), the largest health care provider in rural Haiti, was able to provide some emergency care from its ten hospitals and clinics, all of which were outside the capital and undamaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] MINUSTAH had over 9,000 uniformed peacekeepers deployed to the area.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Most of these workers were initially involved in the search for survivors at the organization's collapsed headquarters.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The International Charter on Space and Major Disasters was activated, allowing satellite imagery of affected regions to be shared with rescue and aid organizations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Members of social networking sites such as Twitter and Facebook spread messages and pleas to send help.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Facebook was overwhelmed by—and blocked—some users who were sending messages about updates.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The American Red Cross set a record for mobile donations, raising US$7 million in 24 hours when they allowed people to send US$10 donations by text messages.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Some online poker sites hosted poker tournaments with tournament fees, prizes or both going to disaster relief charities.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Google Earth updated its coverage of Port-au-Prince on 17 January, showing the earthquake-ravaged city.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Local and state agencies in South Florida, together with the US government, began implementing a plan ("Operation Vigilant Sentry") for a mass migration from the Caribbean that had been laid out in 2003.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Several orphanages were destroyed in the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] After the process for the adoption of 400 children by families in the US and the Netherlands was expedited, Unicef and SOS Children urged an immediate halt to adoptions from Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Jasmine Whitbread, chief executive of Save the Children said: "The vast majority of the children currently on their own still have family members alive who will be desperate to be reunited with them and will be able to care for them with the right support.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 29 January 2010, a group of ten American Baptist missionaries from Idaho attempted to cross the Haiti-Dominican Republic border with 33 Haitian children.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The group, known as the New Life Children's Refuge, did not have proper authorization for transporting the children and were arrested on kidnapping charges.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Rescue efforts began in the immediate aftermath of the earthquake, with able-bodied survivors extricating the living and the dead from the rubble of the many buildings that had collapsed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Treatment of the injured was hampered by the lack of hospital and morgue facilities: the Argentine military field hospital, which had been serving MINUSTAH, was the only one available until 13 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Rescue work intensified only slightly with the arrival of doctors, police officers, military personnel and firefighters from various countries two days after the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] From 12 January, the International Committee of the Red Cross, which has been working in Haiti since 1994, focused on bringing emergency assistance to victims of the catastrophe.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] It worked with its partners within the International Red Cross and Red Crescent Movement, particularly the Haitian Red Cross and the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The American Red Cross also spearheaded a mobile donation initiative with Mobile Accord to raise over $2 million within the first 24 hours after the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Médecins Sans Frontières (Doctors Without Borders; MSF) reported that the hospitals that had not been destroyed were overwhelmed by large numbers of seriously injured people.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The hospitals had to perform many amputations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Running short of medical supplies, some teams had to work with any available resources, constructing splints out of cardboard and reusing latex gloves.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Other rescue units had to withdraw as night fell, amid security fears.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Over 3,000 people had been treated by Médecins Sans Frontières as of 18 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Ophelia Dahl, director of Partners in Health, reported, "there are hundreds of thousands of injured people.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] An MSF aircraft carrying a field hospital was repeatedly turned away by US air traffic controllers, who had assumed control at Toussaint L'Ouverture International Airport.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Four other MSF aircraft were also turned away.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In a 19 January press release MSF said, "It is like working in a war situation.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] We don't have any more morphine to manage pain for our patients.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] We cannot accept that planes carrying lifesaving medical supplies and equipment continue to be turned away while our patients die.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Priority must be given to medical supplies entering the country." First responders voiced frustration with the number of relief trucks sitting unused at the airport.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Aid workers blamed US-controlled airport operations for prioritising the transportation of security troops over rescuers and supplies; evacuation policies favouring citizens of certain nations were also criticised.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The airport staff was strengthened in order to support 100 landings a day, compared to the 35 a day that the airport gets during normal operation.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A spokesman for the joint task force running the airport confirmed that, though more flights were requesting landing slots, none was being turned away.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Brazilian Foreign Minister Celso Amorim and French Minister of State for Cooperation Alain Joyandet criticised the perceived preferential treatment for US aid arriving at the airport.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] A spokesman for the French Ministry of Foreign Affairs said that the French government had not protested officially with regard to the management of the airport.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] US officials acknowledged that coordination of the relief effort is central to Haitian recovery.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] President Préval asked for calm coordination between assisting nations without mutual accusations.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Based on US Air Force logs documenting activity at the airport, the Associated Press largely disproved the claim that the US held up aid in favor of military flights.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The US military initially gave priority to military units in order to secure the airport, distribute aid, and provide security, but after that, incoming relief flights were cleared or rejected on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] According to a US Air Force captain who had coordinated flight schedules, nearly all groups sending aid insisted their shipment was urgent.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Those flights that were rejected were diverted to the Dominican Republic, and their cargoes were unloaded and taken to Haiti by land.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] At the peak of the relief efforts, the airport was in a state of chaos.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Normally, the airport, with a single runway and 10 spaces for large planes, handled 20 flights a day.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] After the earthquake struck, hundreds of planes rushed to Haiti without designated landing times.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On average, a plane would land or take off every two minutes.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The situation was complicated by the lack of room on ramps for planes to unload their cargo, and some planes did not have enough fuel to leave.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] While the Port-au-Prince airport ramp has spaces for more than a dozen airliners, in the days following the quake, it sometimes served nearly 40 at once, creating serious delays.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The supply backup at the airport was expected to ease as the apron management improved, and when the perceived need for heavy security diminished.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Airport congestion was reduced on 18 January when the United Nations and US forces formally agreed to prioritise humanitarian flights over security reinforcement.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] By 14 January, more than 20 countries had sent military personnel to the country, with Canada, the United States, and the Dominican Republic providing the largest contingents.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The supercarrier USS *Carl Vinson* arrived at maximum possible speed on 15 January with 600,000 emergency food rations, 100,000 ten-litre water containers, and an enhanced wing of 19 helicopters; 130,000 litres of drinking water were transferred to shore on the first day.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The helicopter carrier USS *Bataan* sailed with three large dock landing ships and two survey/salvage vessels, to create a "sea base" for the rescue effort.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] They were joined by the French Navy vessel *Francis Garnier* on 16 January, the same day the hospital ship USNS *Comfort* and guided-missile cruiser USS *Bunker Hill* left for Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Another large French vessel was later ordered to Haiti, the amphibious transport dock *Siroco*.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] International rescue efforts were restricted by traffic congestion and blocked roads.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Although US Secretary of Defense Robert Gates had previously ruled out dropping food and water by air as too dangerous, by 16 January, US helicopters were distributing aid by drops to areas impossible to reach by land.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In Jacmel, a city of 50,000, the mayor claimed that 70 percent of the homes had been damaged and that the quake had killed 300 to 500 people and left some 4,000 injured.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The small airstrip suffered damage rendering it unusable for supply flights until 20 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Canadian navy vessel HMCS *Halifax* was deployed to the area on 18 January; the Canadians joined Colombian rescue workers, Chilean doctors, a French mobile clinic, and Sri Lankan relief workers who had already responded to calls for aid.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] About 64,000 people living in the three adjacent agricultural communities of Durissy, Morne a Chandelle, and Les Palmes were relatively unharmed because most of the people were working in the fields when the quakes struck.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] All their churches, chapels, and at least 8,000 homes were destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 17 January 2010, British search and rescue teams were the first to reach Léogane, the town at the epicenter of the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Canadian ship HMCS *Athabaskan* reached the area on 19 January, and by 20 January some 250–300 Canadian personnel were assisting relief efforts in the town.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] By 19 January, staff of the International Red Cross had also managed to reach the town, which they described as "severely damaged ... the people there urgently need assistance." By 20 January they had reached Petit-Goâve as well, where they set up two first-aid posts and distributed first-aid kits.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Over the first weekend 130,000 food packets and 70,000 water containers were distributed to Haitians, as safe landing areas and distribution centers such as golf courses were secured.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Nearly 2,000 rescuers had arrived from 43 different groups, with 161 search dogs; the airport had handled 250 tons of relief supplies by the end of the weekend.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Reports from Sunday showed a record-breaking number of successful rescues, with at least 12 survivors pulled from Port-au-Prince's rubble, bringing the total number of rescues to 110.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In an interview on 21 January, Leo Merores, Haiti's ambassador to the UN, said that he expected the port to be fully functional again within two weeks.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The US Navy listed its resources in the area as "17 ships, 48 helicopters and 12 fixed-wing aircraft" in addition to 10,000 sailors and Marines.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The Navy had conducted 336 air deliveries, delivered 32,400 US gallons (123,000 L) of water, 532,440 bottles of water, 111,082 meals and 9,000 lb (4,100 kg) of medical supplies by 20 January.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 22 January the UN and United States formalised the coordination of relief efforts by signing an agreement giving the US responsibility for the ports, airports and roads, and making the UN and Haitian authorities responsible for law and order.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The UN stated that it had resisted formalising the organization of the relief effort to allow as much leeway as possible for those wishing to assist in the relief effort, but with the new agreement "we're leaving that emergency phase behind".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The UN also urged organizations to coordinate aid efforts through its mission in Haiti to allow for better scheduling of the arrival of supplies.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 23 January the Haitian government officially called off the search for survivors, and most search and rescue teams began to prepare to leave the country.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] However, as late as 8 February 2010, survivors were still being discovered, as in the case of Evan Muncie, 28, found in the rubble of a grocery store.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 5 February, ten Baptist missionaries from Idaho led by Laura Silsby were charged with criminal association and kidnapping for trying to smuggle 33 children out of Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] The missionaries claimed they were rescuing orphaned children but investigations revealed that more than 20 of the children had been taken from their parents after they were told the children would have a better life in America.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] In an interview, Kenneth Merten, the United States Ambassador to Haiti, stated that the US justice system would not interfere and that "the Haitian justice system will do what it has to do." By 9 March 2010, all but Silsby were deported and she remained incarcerated.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] Social networking organizations such as Crisis Camp Haiti were developed to aid in the structure and coordination of relief efforts in Haiti and future catastrophic events as well.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] By 4 March, the American Red Cross, in conjunction with Mobile Accord's mGive platform, had raised a total of $50 million for victims of the Haiti earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] James Eberhard of Mobile Accord stated that $32.5 million of the donations came from text giving.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p01] On 10 April, due to the potential threat of mudslides and flooding from the upcoming rainy season, the Haitian government began operations to move thousands of refugees to a more secure location north of the capital.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] US President Barack Obama announced that former presidents Bill Clinton, who was the UN special envoy to Haiti at the time, and George W.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Bush would coordinate efforts to raise funds for Haiti's recovery.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Secretary of State Hillary Clinton visited Haiti on 16 January to survey the damage and stated that US$48 million had been raised already in the US to help Haiti recover.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Following the meeting with Secretary Clinton, President Préval stated that the highest priorities in Haiti's recovery were establishing a working government, clearing roads, and ensuring the streets were cleared of bodies to improve sanitary conditions.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] US Vice President Joe Biden stated on 16 January that President Obama "does not view this as a humanitarian mission with a life cycle of a month.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] This will still be on our radar screen long after it's off the crawler at CNN.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] A remake of the song "Wavin' Flag" by Somalian-Canadian singer K'naan became a charity single in Canada, reaching number 1 on the "Canadian Hot 100" chart.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The song was later chosen as Coca-Cola's promotional anthem for the 2010 FIFA World Cup hosted by South Africa.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Trade and Industry Minister Josseline Colimon Fethiere estimated that the earthquake's toll on the Haitian economy would be massive, with one in five jobs lost.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In response to the earthquake, foreign governments offered badly needed financial aid.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The European Union promised €330 million for emergency and long-term aid.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Brazil announced R$375 million for long-term recovery aid, R$25 million of which was in immediate funds.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The United Kingdom's Secretary of State for International Development Douglas Alexander called the result of the earthquake an "almost unprecedented level of devastation", and committed the UK to £20 million in aid, while France promised €10 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Italy announced it would waive repayment of the €40 million it had loaned to Haiti, and the World Bank waived the country's debt repayments for five years.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On 14 January, the US government announced it would give US$100 million to the aid effort and pledged that the people of Haiti "will not be forgotten".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In the aftermath of the earthquake, the government of Canada announced that it would match the donations of Canadians up to a total of C$50 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Canadians were able to donate through the Humanitarian Coalition which distributed funds to partner organizations working in the field.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] During this time the Humanitarian Coalition raised over C$15 Million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] After a United Nations call for help for the people affected by the earthquake, Canada pledged an additional C$60 million in aid on 19 January 2010, bringing Canada's total contribution to C$135 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On top of matching donations, International Co-operation Minister Bev Oda pledged an additional C$290 million in long-term relief to be spent between 2010 and 2012, including C$8 million in debt relief to Haiti, part of a broader cancellation of the country's overall World Bank debt.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The government's commitment to provide C$550 million in aid and debt relief and Canadians' individual donations amount to a total of C$770 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In addition to Canada's federal government, the governments of several of the provinces and territories of Canada also announced that they would provide immediate emergency aid to Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On 18 January 2010, the province of Quebec, whose largest city – Montreal – houses the country's largest Haitian diaspora, pledged C$3 million in emergency aid.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] President Abdoulaye Wade of Senegal offered interested Haitians free land in Senegal; depending on how many respond to the offer, this could include up to an entire region.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Around 2,000 Haitians applied for this offer.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In October 2010, 163 of these applicants arrived in Senegal.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] They are Haitian students who were selected to continue their education in Senegal.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Port-au-Prince, according to an international studies professor at the University of Miami, was ill-equipped before the disaster to sustain the number of people who had migrated there from the countryside over the past ten years to find work.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] After the earthquake, thousands of Port-au-Prince residents began returning to the rural towns they came from.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On 25 January a one-day conference was held in Montreal to assess the relief effort and discuss further plans.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Prime Minister Bellerive told delegates from 20 countries that Haiti would need "massive support" for its recovery from the international community.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] A donors' conference was expected to be held at the UN headquarters in New York in March, however, took more than three months to hold the UN conference.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The 26-member international Interim Haiti Reconstruction Commission, headed by Bill Clinton and Haitian Prime Minister Jean-Max Bellerive, convened in June 2010.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] That committee is overseeing the US$5.3 billion pledged internationally for the first two years of Haiti's reconstruction.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The commission was critiqued by Haitian groups for lacking Haitian civil society representation and accountability mechanisms.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Half the representation on the commission was given to foreigners who effectively bought their seats by pledging certain amounts of money.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] An international development consultant contracted by the commission was quoted as saying, "Look, you have to realize the IHRC [commission] was not intended to work as a structure or entity for Haiti or Haitians.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The Netherlands sponsored a project, called Radio555.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The Dutch radio channels 3FM, Radio 538 and Radio Veronica all broadcast under the name of Radio555, funded by a contribution of €80 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Several organizations of the US building industry and government, such as the Department of Homeland Security and the International Code Council, among others, reported that they were compiling a "Haiti Toolkit" coordinated by the National Institute of Building Sciences.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The toolkit would comprise building technology resources and best practices for consideration by the Haitian government with the goal of creating a more resilient infrastructure to prevent future losses of life.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Immediately following the earthquake, Real Medicine Foundation began providing medical staffing, in-kind medical supplies and strategic coordination to help meet the surging needs of the health crisis on the ground.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On 15 January 2011, the Catholic Relief Services announced a US$200 million, five-year relief and reconstruction program that covers shelter, health, livelihoods, and child protection among its program areas.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Six months after the quake as much as 98% of the rubble remained uncleared.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] An estimated 26 million cubic yards (20 million cubic meters) remained, making most of the capital impassable, and thousands of bodies remained in the rubble.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The number of people in relief camps of tents and tarps since the quake was 1.6 million, and almost no transitional housing had been built.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Most of the camps had no electricity, running water, or sewage disposal, and the tents were beginning to fall apart.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Crime in the camps was widespread, especially against women and girls.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Between 23 major charities, US$1.1 billion had been collected for Haiti for relief efforts, but only two percent of the money had been released.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] According to a CBS report, US$3.1 billion had been pledged for humanitarian aid and was used to pay for field hospitals, plastic tarps, bandages, and food, plus salaries, transportation and upkeep of relief workers.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] By May 2010, enough aid had been raised internationally to give each displaced family a cheque for US$37,000.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In July 2010, CNN returned to Port-au-Prince and reported, "It looks like the quake just happened yesterday", and Imogen Wall, spokeswoman for the United Nations office of humanitarian affairs in Haiti, said that "six months from that time it may still look the same".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Haitian grassroots groups advocated for the government to fulfill the right to housing as designated in the Haitian constitution, and for donor governments to support this as well.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] They also worked to push the international community to recognize the wave of evictions from camps that started as early as three months after the earthquake and to put protections in place, but little was done in response.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In September 2010 there were over one million refugees still living in tents, and the humanitarian situation was characterized as still being in the emergency phase, according to the Apostolic Nuncio to Haiti, Archbishop Bernard Auza.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] He went on to say that the number was rising instead of diminishing, and reported that the state had decided to first rebuild downtown Port-au-Prince and a new government center, but reconstruction had not yet begun.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In October 2010, Refugees International characterized the aid agencies as dysfunctional and inexperienced saying,"The people of Haiti are still living in a state of emergency, with a humanitarian response that appears paralyzed".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] It was reported that gang leaders and land owners were intimidating the displaced and that sexual, domestic, and gang violence in and around the camps was rising.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] They claimed that rape of Haitian women and girls who had been living in camps since the January earthquake was increasing, in part, because the United Nations wasn't doing enough to protect them.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In October, a cholera epidemic broke out, probably introduced by United Nations peacekeepers.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Cholera most often affects poor countries with limited access to clean water and proper sanitation.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] By the end of 2010, more than 3,333 had died at a rate of about 50 deaths a day.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In January 2011, one year after the quake, Oxfam published a report on the status of the recovery.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] According to the report, relief and recovery were at a standstill due to government inaction and indecision on the part of the donor countries.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] According to a UNICEF report, "Still today more than one million people remain displaced, living in crowded camps where livelihoods, shelter and services are still hardly sufficient for children to stay healthy".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Amnesty International reported that armed men were preying with impunity on girls and women in displacement camps, worsening the trauma of victims who have lost homes, livelihoods and loved ones.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] She blamed the international community for abandoning its commitments.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In January 2012, two years since the quake, figures released by the United Nations show that of the nearly US$4.5 billion pledged for reconstruction projects in 2010 and 2011, only 43% has been delivered.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Venezuela and the US, which promised the major share of reconstruction funds, have disbursed only 24% and 30%, respectively.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Japan and Finland are among the few donors to have fully met their pledges.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The data shows that some crucial sectors face particularly large funding gaps.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In 2010 and 2011, for example, donors disbursed just US$125 million of the US$311 million in grants allocated to agriculture projects, and only US$108 million of the US$315 million in grants allocated to health projects.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Only 6% of bilateral aid for reconstruction projects has gone through Haitian institutions, and less than 1% of relief funding has gone through the government of Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] A January 2012 Oxfam report said that a half a million Haitians remained homeless, still living under tarps and in tents.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Watchdog groups have criticized the reconstruction process saying that part of the problem is that charities spent a considerable amount of money on "soaring rents, board members' needs, overpriced supplies and imported personnel," the *Miami Herald* reported.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] "A lot of good work was done; the money clearly didn't all get squandered," but, "A lot just wasn't responding to needs on the ground.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Millions were spent on ad campaigns telling people to wash their hands.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The Institute for Justice & Democracy in Haiti, Let Haiti Live, and the Center for Constitutional Rights have recommended immediate changes to recovery efforts to ensure that critical human rights concerns are addressed.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] A report found that, "The conditions in the displaced persons camps are abysmal, particularly for women and girls who too often are victims of gender-based violence".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] On 25 August 2012, recovery was hampered due to Tropical Storm Isaac impacting Haiti's southern peninsula.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] There it caused flooding and 29 deaths according to local reporting.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] As a result of the 2010 earthquake, more than 400,000 Haitians continue to live in tents and experienced the storm without adequate shelter.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In late October, with over 370,000 still living in tent camps, a second tropical storm, Hurricane Sandy, killed 55 and left large portions of Haiti under water.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] According to the International Monetary Fund, more than half of the 10,000,000 cubic metres (13,000,000 yd3) of debris have been removed, and 20% of it has been recycled.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The 2010 cholera outbreak has continued.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Centers for Disease Control and Prevention it is considered the worst epidemic of cholera since the 1994 outbreak in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (called Zaire at that time).
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] By August 2013, it had killed over 8,231 Haitians and hospitalized hundreds of thousands more.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] More than 6% of Haitians have had the disease.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Care of cholera patients remains inadequate with much now done in tent facilities with rows of cots for patient treatment.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] By the beginning of the year only a small part—$215 million—of the total funds collected for aid had been spent on permanent housing, with most of it—$1.2 billion—going for short-term solutions including tent camps, temporary shelters, and cash grants that paid a year's rent.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] A 2013 survey disclosed that of the 1.5 million Haitians living in camps following the quake, about 279,000 remained in a total of 352 camps.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] 15% of the camps had no basic protection services, and 48% no health services.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] While 20% lacked functioning toilets, this is higher than the population outside tent cities, where 50% lack toilets.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Many camps remained at a risk for flooding and more than a third of the camps (108) were at risk for evictions.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In 2015, NPR and ProPublica investigated the disappearance of US$500 million donated to the American Red Cross for earthquake relief, earlier described by the charity as the result of "one of the most successful fundraisers ever".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Despite the claims of the American Red Cross that 130,000 homes had been built, the investigation discovered that only six had been built.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The investigation reviewed "hundreds" of pages of internal documents and interviewed "more than a dozen" former and current staff members, investigating the organization's claim that 4.5 million Haitians had been helped "back on their feet".
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Joel Boutroue, a Haitian government advisor, said that this number would cover "100 percent of the urban area", and observed that it would mean the Red Cross had served every city in Haiti.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Numerous other claims did not hold up under investigation.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] NPR found that the project was riddled with "multiple staffing changes", bureaucratic delays and a language barrier, as many of the Red Cross officials spoke neither French nor Haitian Creole.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] General counsel for the American Red Cross, David Meltzer, provided investigators with the NGO's official statistics, but would not elaborate on them.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The public affairs office of the Red Cross disputed NPR and ProPublica's claims in an email, and claimed that their investigative report could cause an international incident.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] By June the American Red Cross had transferred the rebuilding efforts to the Haitian Red Cross.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In 2016, Haiti was struck by Hurricane Matthew which leveled entire communities and caused an upsurge in the ongoing cholera epidemic which was introduced to the island by United Nations peacekeepers.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] As of March 2017, around 7% of Haiti's population (around 800,665 people) have been affected with cholera, and 9,480 Haitians have died.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] In 2017, the United Nations reported that 2.5 million Haitians were still in need of humanitarian aid.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Humanitarian Coordinator Mourad Wahba said, "There are still about 55,000 people in camps and makeshift camps.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] Many are still living in unsanitary conditions due to displacement caused by the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2010-haiti-earthquake-p02] The Haiti 2010 earthquake has been depicted in the novel *God Loves Haiti*, by Dimitry Elias Léger.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The **Joplin tornado** was an extremely devastating EF5 tornado that struck the city of Joplin, Missouri during the early evening hours of May 22, 2011, causing catastrophic damage to it and surrounding regions.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As part of a larger late-May sequence of tornadic activity, the extremely violent tornado began just west of Joplin at about 5:34 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (UTC–05:00) and quickly reached a peak width of nearly 1 mile (1.6 km) as it tracked through the southern part of the city, before later impacting rural Jasper and Newton counties and dissipating after 38 minutes on the ground at 6:12 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado was on the ground for a total of 21.62 miles (34.79 km).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado devastated a large portion of the city of Joplin, damaging nearly 8,000 buildings and destroying over 4,000 houses.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The damage—which included major facilities like one of Joplin's two hospitals as well as much of its basic infrastructure—amounted to a total of $2.8 billion (equivalent to about $4 billion today), making the Joplin tornado the costliest single tornado in U.S. history.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The insurance payout was the highest in Missouri history, breaking the previous $2 billion record from the hailstorm of April 10, 2001.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado was the fifth out of six total EF5 tornadoes that occurred in 2011, with four having occurred a month earlier during the 2011 Super Outbreak, and only two days before the same outbreak sequence produced another EF5 tornado in El Reno, Oklahoma on May 24.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Overall, the tornado killed 158 people (including eight indirect deaths) and injured some 1,150 others, making it the deadliest tornado of 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] It ranks as the deadliest tornado in Missouri in addition to being one of the deadliest in the United States, having the highest death toll since the Glazier–Woodward F5 tornado in Texas and Oklahoma in 1947 and the seventh-deadliest overall in the U.S.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] It was the first F5/EF5 tornado to occur in Missouri since May 20, 1957, when an F5 tornado destroyed several suburbs of Kansas City, and only the second F5/EF5 tornado in Missouri since 1950.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] It was the third tornado to strike Joplin since May 5, 1971.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In the aftermath, President Barack Obama toured the city on May 29, speaking at a memorial service for the victims.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] He would also deliver the commencement address at Joplin High School a year later in 2012.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Services were set up to help rebuild, with most of the town having businesses reopen as well as new ones being built by 2018.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Additionally, the tornado helped inspire FEMA to create the Waffle House Index for disaster preparations as a result of some locations remaining open during the storm.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] On the evening of May 21, 2011, an area of low pressure centered over western South Dakota.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] This feature, in addition to steep lapse rates and dewpoints above 60 °F (16 °C), was conducive to the supercell development later in the day.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Very large hail was forecasted, but the tornado threat was predicted to remain isolated.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (1300 UTC), the National Weather Service (NWS) Storm Prediction Center (SPC) issued a slight risk of severe storms for much of the upper Plains and the Midwest.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (1300 UTC) on May 22, forecasters at the SPC realized that a more intense weather outbreak was likely to occur, and upgraded a large swath of the Midwest to a moderate risk.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The system was forecast to evolve into a wave early Monday morning as a trough strengthened from the western United States.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] At the surface, a cold front was forecast to pass through the region later in the day, while a dryline was forecast to intersect the cold front in Kansas.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] These features, accompanied by the low-pressure system, encouraged very strong storm development along the cold front.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (1630 UTC) updated outlook, certainty had grown stronger that a major severe weather event would occur that afternoon.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A public severe weather outlook was issued at this time, and the outlook stated that severe weather was expected that afternoon, with tornadoes, large hail and strong winds all named as threats.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (1830 UTC), four hours prior to the tornado, the SPC issued a tornado watch for southwestern Missouri, to remain in effect until 9:00 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The watch predicted "explosive thunderstorm development," with a "strong tornado or two possible." Thunderstorms began developing between 2:00 and 3:00 p.m. over southeast Kansas and quickly became severe.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As thunderstorm development continued moving to the east, forecasters became more concerned about imminent tornado development.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A tornado warning west of Joplin that eventually produced the EF5 tornado was first issued at 5:17 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (22:17 UTC), 17 minutes before it touched ground and 19 minutes before it entered the city of Joplin.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado first touched down in Newton County, Missouri, just east of the Missouri–Kansas state line, approximately one-half mile (0.80 km) southwest of the intersection of South Central City Road and 32nd Street, at 5:34 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Eyewitnesses and storm chasers reported multiple vortices rotating around the parent circulation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Here, the tornado downed several large trees at EF0 intensity.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Civil defense sirens sounded in Joplin twenty minutes before the tornado struck, in response to the tornado warning issued at 5:17 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (22:17 UTC) for northwestern Newton and southwestern Jasper counties in Missouri, and southeastern portions of Cherokee County, Kansas, but many Joplin residents did not heed the warning or the sirens.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado moved east-northeast and strengthened to EF1 intensity as it continued through rural areas towards Joplin, snapping trees and power poles and damaging outbuildings.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado then widened and tracked into the more densely populated southwest corner of the city near the Twin Hills Country Club.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado heavily damaged several homes at a subdivision in this area at up to EF3 strength before continuing to move through another subdivision just east of Iron Gates Road.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Numerous homes were destroyed and multiple vehicles tossed around, some of which were thrown onto or rolled into homes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado reached EF4 intensity just before crossing S.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The now massive and wedge-shaped tornado then crossed S.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (22:38 UTC), producing its first area of EF4 damage just four minutes after touching down, as several small but well-built commercial buildings were flattened.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] One person was killed after they were ejected from their car as the tornado crossed the road.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Further strengthening resulted in the tornado reaching EF5 intensity shortly afterwards.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Consistent EF4 to EF5 damage was noted east of S.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Schifferdecker Ave. and continued through most of southern Joplin.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Numerous homes, businesses, and medical buildings were flattened in this area, with concrete walls crushed into the foundations.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A large steel-reinforced step and floor structure leading to a completely destroyed medical building was "deflected upward several inches and cracked".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Steel trusses from some of the buildings were "rolled up like paper", and deformation or twisting of the main support beams was noted.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Multiple vehicles were thrown and mangled or wrapped around trees nearby.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Several 300-pound concrete parking stops anchored with rebar were torn from a parking lot in this area and thrown up to 60 yards (55 m) away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Iowa State University wind engineer Partha Sarkar calculated the force needed to remove the parking stops from the lot and found that winds exceeding 200 mph (320 km/h) would have been required.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Damage became widespread and catastrophic at and around the nearby St.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] John's Regional Medical Center, which lost nearly every window on three sides, interior walls, ceilings, and part of its roof; its life flight helicopter was also blown away and destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Loss of backup power caused five fatalities, and the building was damaged so severely that it was deemed structurally compromised and later torn down.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to the NWS office in Springfield, Missouri, such extreme structural damage to such a large and well-built structure likely indicated winds at or exceeding 200 mph (320 km/h).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Vehicles in the hospital parking lot were thrown into the air and mangled beyond recognition, including a semi-truck that was tossed 125 yards (114 m) and wrapped completely around a debarked tree.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Small pieces of debris from the hospital, including X-rays, medical reports, and dental records, were found in Greene and Polk counties many miles to the east.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Wind-rowing of debris was noted in this area, and more concrete parking stops were removed from the St.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Virtually every house near McClelland Boulevard and 26th Street was flattened; some were swept completely away, and trees sustained severe debarking.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As the tornado tracked eastward, it maintained EF5 strength as it crossed Main Street (Route 43) between 20th and 26th Streets.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] It heavily damaged every business along that stretch and virtually destroyed several institutional buildings.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Despite destroying entire neighborhoods in the area with some more homes swept away, the tornado tracked just south of downtown, narrowly missing it.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] At some residences, reinforced concrete porches were deformed or, in some cases, completely torn away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Numerous vehicles were tossed up to several blocks, and a few homeowners never located their vehicles.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A large church, a nursing home, Franklin Technology Center, St.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Mary's Catholic Church and School, and Joplin High School were all destroyed along this corridor.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The Greenbriar Nursing Home was completely leveled, with 21 fatalities occurring there alone, with dozens of fatalities occurring elsewhere in this area as well.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Nobody was in the high school at the time, as the graduation ceremonies held about three miles (4.8 km) to the north at Missouri Southern State University had concluded shortly before the storm.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Pieces of cardboard were found embedded in stucco walls that remained standing at Joplin High School.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Steel beams and pieces of fencing were deeply embedded into the ground in fields near the high school, steel fence posts were bent to the ground in opposite directions, and a school bus was thrown into a nearby bus garage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As the tornado crossed Connecticut Avenue further to the east, it destroyed several large apartment buildings which resulted in 14 fatalities, along with a Dillons grocery store, and a bank.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Only the concrete safety deposit box vault remained at the bank, and a wooden 2×4 beam was found speared completely through a concrete curb at one location.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado then approached Rangeline Road, the main commercial strip in the eastern part of Joplin, affecting additional neighborhoods along 20th Street.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The now heavily rain-wrapped tornado continued at EF5 intensity as it crossed Range Line Road.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In that corridor between about 13th and 32nd Streets, the tornado continued producing catastrophic damage as it reached its widest point nearly one mile (1.6 km) across.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As the tornado struck a Pizza Hut on South Range Line Road, store manager Christopher Lucas herded four employees and 15 customers into a walk-in freezer.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] With difficulty closing the door, he wrapped a bungee cord holding the door shut around his arm until he was sucked out and killed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado completely destroyed a Walmart supercenter, a Home Depot, and numerous other businesses and restaurants in the area, many of which were flattened.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Numerous metal roof trusses were torn from the Home Depot building and were found broken and mangled in nearby fields, and cars originally parked at the Home Depot parking lot were found hundreds of yards away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Asphalt was scoured from parking lots at Walmart and a nearby pizza restaurant, and large tractor-trailers were thrown up to 200 yards (180 m) away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] An Academy Sports + Outdoors store along Range Line sustained major structural damage, and a chair was found impaled legs-first through an exterior stucco wall there.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A nearby three-story apartment complex was also devastated, and two cell phone towers collapsed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In this area, numerous cars were thrown and piled on top of each other, 100-pound (45 kg) manhole covers were removed from roads and thrown, and a Pepsi distribution plant was completely leveled.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Additional calculations with regards to the manhole covers by Partha Sarkar revealed that winds had to have exceeded 200 miles per hour (320 km/h) for the manhole covers to be removed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Twenty fatalities occurred in this area, and the damage was rated as EF5.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Extreme damage continued in the area of Duquesne Road in southeast Joplin.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Homes and the industrial park near the corner of 20th and Duquesne was especially hard hit with nearly every building flattened.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Several large warehouse structures were swept cleanly from their foundations, and several heavy industrial vehicles were thrown up to 400 yards (370 m) away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The last area of EF5 damage occurred in the industrial park, and a nearby Fastrip gas station and convenience store was completely destroyed – a famous first-person video of the direct hit was recorded by a man sheltering in the beer cooler here.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Many homes were destroyed further to the east at EF3 to EF4 strength in a nearby subdivision, and East Middle School sustained major damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado then continued on an east to east-southeast trajectory towards I-44 where it weakened; nonetheless, vehicles were blown off the highway and mangled near US 71 (exit 11) (now I-49) interchange.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The damage at and around the interchange was rated EF2 to EF3.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The weakening tornado continued to track into the rural areas of southeastern Jasper County and northeastern Newton County where damage was generally minor to moderate, with trees, mobile homes, outbuildings, and frame homes damaged at EF0 to EF1 strength.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado lifted east of Diamond at 6:12 p.m.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] CDT (23:12 UTC), according to aerial surveys.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The total track length was 21.62 miles (34.79 km) long, and the tornado was up to 0.75–1 mile (1.21–1.61 km) across at its widest point.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A total of 158 people were killed, and over 1,150 others were injured along the path.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A separate EF2 tornado touched down near Wentworth from the same supercell about 25 miles (40 km) east-southeast of Joplin, beginning roughly 10 minutes before the dissipation of this tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A preliminary survey of the tornado damage by the NWS office in Springfield began on May 23.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The initial survey confirmed a violent tornado rated as a high-end EF4.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Subsequent damage surveys, however, found evidence of more intense damage, and so the tornado was upgraded to an EF5 with estimated winds over 200 mph (320 km/h), peaking at 225 to 250 mph (360 to 400 km/h).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The scope of the damage was immense: according to the local branch of the American Red Cross, about 25% of Joplin was destroyed, though emergency officials reported some level of damage to about 75% of the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A week after the tornado, Joplin's mayor estimated that 25% of the businesses licensed in the city were damaged or destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Official accountings of the precise number of buildings damaged or destroyed vary somewhat.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) technical report, in total 7,964 buildings were damaged in Joplin, including 7,411 residential buildings and 553 non-residential.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] At least 3,734 of those buildings (including 3,181 of the residential and all 553 of the non-residential buildings) sustained so much damage as to be considered destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to a Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) study, 8,264 homes were impacted, and of those, 3,884 were "significantly damaged" and 4,380 were destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado severely damaged critical infrastructure in the city, hampering emergency response and recovery efforts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Approximately 4,000 electricity distribution poles were damaged, more than 110 miles (180 km) of distribution line brought down, 135 transmission towers "affected," and an electrical substation in the path of the tornado was completely destroyed (two more were damaged, but reparably so).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In the immediate aftermath of the storm, approximately 20,000 people were left without power, and those with homes left intact could not get it restored until 10–12 days later, when their dwellings were approved for safe occupancy.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The ultimate cost of rebuilding Joplin's damaged electricity system was calculated at $25.7 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado also caused about 4,000 leaks in water service lines, dropping Joplin's water system pressure below operating level and necessitating a block-by-block effort to find and repair the service line leaks, with a water boil order issued for the entire city in the meantime.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Water pressure was returned to normal outside of the damage area within 48 hours, and the water boil order was lifted after five and a half days.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Approximately 3,500 gas meters and 55,000 feet (17,000 m) of gas main were damaged, and it took two weeks to stem every gas leak; some damaged mains could not be shut off because they served critical facilities like Freeman Health System, the lone remaining hospital in Joplin.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In east Joplin, 3,000–5,000 pounds (1,400–2,300 kg) of anhydrous ammonia was released from a valve at a trucking facility and quickly contained; no significant toxic releases occurred.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] With 21 cell towers down and fiber cables damaged, cellular communications—voice calls in particular, text messages less so—were heavily impeded.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Temporary mobile cell towers were deployed by wireless carriers to fill the gap within 24 hours.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] By May 24, three towers owned by AT&T and Sprint had been restored.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] An early estimate from catastrophe risk modeling firm Eqecat, Inc. placed the insured losses from the tornado at $1–3 billion USD.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] By mid-June, more than 19,000 insurance claims had been filed, a number that rose to 61,000, with a total payout of more than $2 billion—31% going to homeowners and 5% to those who lost vehicles.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The impact on the insurance industry was not so much due to the number of claims, but the cumulative effect of such a large number of total losses.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] More than 2,500 local people employed in insurance were involved in some capacity.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] It was presumed that State Farm would assume the largest share of these losses, having market share of 27% for homeowners insurance and 21% for automobile insurance.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The $2.8 billion in damage is the largest amount for a tornado since the Tuscaloosa-Birmingham EF4 which occurred in the same year.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As of May 2013, the official death toll from NWS was listed at 158 while the City of Joplin listed the death toll at 161 (158 direct).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The list was up to 162, until one man's injuries were found to be unrelated to the event.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In one indirect fatality, a policeman was struck by lightning and killed while assisting with recovery and cleanup efforts the day after the storm.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Another five indirect fatalities occurred after a disease outbreak of mucormycosis infected 13 people, possibly 18 people.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Shortly after the tornado, authorities had listed 1,300 people as missing, but the number quickly dwindled as they were accounted for.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Many people were reported to have been trapped in destroyed houses.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Seventeen people were rescued from the rubble the day after the tornado struck.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Of 146 sets of remains recovered from the rubble, 134 victims had been positively identified by June 1.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] This total included four sets of partial remains, some of which may have been from a single person.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] On June 2, it was announced that four more victims had died.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] John's Regional Medical Center was struck by the tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Five of those deaths were patients on ventilators who died after the building lost power and a backup generator did not work.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The sixth fatality was a hospital visitor.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The *Joplin Globe* reported that 54% of the people killed died in their residences, 32% died in non-residential areas and 14% died in vehicles or outdoors.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Joplin officials after the tornado announced plans to require hurricane ties or other fasteners between the houses and their foundations (devices add about US$600 to the construction costs).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Officials rejected a proposal to require concrete basements in new houses.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Officials noted that as of 2009, only 28% of Joplin's new homes had basements, compared with 38% two decades before.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] At least 1,150 people were injured severely enough to seek treatment at regional hospitals.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Injuries ranged from cuts and bruises to impalement by large debris.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Officials said they rescued 944 pets and reunited 292 with owners.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In 2013, the American Society of Civil Engineers published a study disputing the tornado's initial EF5 rating, based on surveying damage on over 150 structures within a six-mile segment of the storm's path.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to the report, over 83% of the damage was caused by wind speeds of 135 mph (217 km/h) or less, the maximum wind speed of an EF2 tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] An additional 13% was caused by EF3 wind speeds, and 3% was consistent with EF4 winds.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The study found no damage consistent with wind speeds over 200 mph (320 km/h), the minimum threshold of an EF5 tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Researchers concluded that the inability to find EF5 damage was due to the absence of construction standards that were able to determine the necessary wind speeds.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The NWS office in Springfield stated that their survey teams found only a small area of EF5 structural damage, and that it could have easily been missed in the survey (at and around St.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Bill Davis, head of Springfield's NWS office, said that the results of the study "do not surprise me at all," adding that "there was only a very small area of EF5 damage in Joplin...we knew right off the bat there was EF4 damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to a detailed damage survey by Timothy Marshall, a majority of houses were destroyed at winds of EF2-3 strength.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] However, he identified 22 well anchored houses which were assigned EF5 ratings.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Immediately following the disaster, emergency responders were deployed within and to the city for search and rescue efforts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Then Governor Jay Nixon declared a state of emergency for the Joplin area shortly after the tornado hit, and ordered Missouri National Guard troops to the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] By May 23, Missouri Task Force One (consisting of 85 personnel, four dogs, and heavy equipment) arrived and began searching for missing persons.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Five heavy rescue teams were also sent to the city a day later.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Within two days, numerous agencies arrived to assist residents in the recovery process.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The National Guard deployed 191 personnel and placed 2,000 more on standby to be deployed if needed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Due to the severe damage caused by the tornado, the traveling Piccadilly Circus was unable to perform as scheduled.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] As a result, the circus employees brought their two adult elephants to help drag damaged automobiles and other heavy debris out of the streets.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Despite the destruction, two Waffle House locations in Joplin remained open following the tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] This led Federal Emergency Management Agency Administrator Craig Fugate to develop the concept of the Waffle House Index for measuring disaster impact.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In May 2012, the Missouri National Guard released documents showing that four soldiers looted consumer electronics from a ruined Walmart during efforts to locate survivors the day after the tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] According to the investigative memo, they believed the merchandise was going to be destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] All four soldiers were demoted and had letters of reprimand placed in their personnel files, but were never prosecuted, though many civilian looters were.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The Joplin tornado generated an estimated 3 million cubic yards of debris, an amount sufficient to cover a football field 120 stories high.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Removal efforts lasted for months, and at their height more than 410 trucks a day transported debris to landfills in Joplin itself, as well as nearby Galena and Lamar.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado also led to renewed lead contamination on many Joplin properties.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The city spent more than $5 million to clean the properties up using grants from the Environmental Protection Agency, scraping off the topsoil and replacing it with clean soil, and further required that builders in the damage area test for lead and clean it up before construction.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The tornado also highlighted a new form of disaster response, using social media.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] This type of disaster response is now known as Social Media Emergency Management.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] News outlets began aggregating images and video from eyewitnesses shared through social media.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Public citizen-led Facebook groups and web sites coordinated information, needs, and offers.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The results were so effective the project became a finalist in the 2011 Mashable Awards for Best Social Good Cause Campaign.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] President Barack Obama toured the community on May 29, flying into Joplin Regional Airport and speaking at a memorial at the Taylor Performing Arts Center at Missouri Southern State University about two miles (3.2 km) north of the worst of the devastation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Obama had been on a state visit to Europe at the time of the storm.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Members of the controversial Westboro Baptist Church were also scheduled to protest the same day in Joplin, but they did not show up.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] President Obama also delivered the commencement address at Joplin High School on May 21, 2012, a year after the tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] FEMA maintained a large presence in Joplin following the tornado, with as many as 820 employees working in the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] One FEMA undertaking was the construction of 15 temporary housing sites in and around Joplin, which housed 586 families/households at their peak.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] The city, warned by federal officials that it should expect to lose 25% of its population following the tornado, responded quickly and built an average of five houses a week between 2011 and 2022.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Most businesses reopened, and more than 300 new businesses opened between 2011 and early 2016.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In April 2012, Joplin voters approved a $62 million bond to continue constructing new schools and repair damaged existing ones.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Home Depot officials disagreed with the study published by *The Kansas City Star* and said they would use the tilt-up practice when they rebuilt the Joplin store.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] On June 1, the Home Depot said it would have a new temporary 30,000 sq ft (2,800 m2) building erected and operational within two weeks.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In the meantime, it opened for business in the parking lot of its demolished building.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] On June 20, the Home Depot opened a temporary 60,000 sq ft (5,600 m2) building constructed by the company's disaster recovery team.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Within two years, the city's workers and community groups compiled and published "Joplin Pays it Forward" to give recovery advice to other places struck by disasters.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Many homes and businesses have been rebuilt since the tornado.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Joplin High School was reopened on September 2, 2014.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] John's Regional Medical Center (now Mercy Hospital) had to be rebuilt and reopened in 2015.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Eighteen people committed suicide in the wake of the tornado, according to the executive director of the Community Clinic of Southwest Missouri, a co-chair of the city's long-term recovery team.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Calls about domestic violence grew in the year following the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Brian Houston, and Sangwon Lee with the University of Tennessee along with Megan Carnahan and Mansoo Yu with the University of Missouri, published a qualitative case study of survivors from the tornado, in which they described how survivors recovered from "tornado brain".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In the paper, they stated approximately 41% of the residents of Joplin were directly impacted by the tornado and that the tornado lead to "various mental health disorders such as depression, anxiety, and post-traumatic stress disorder".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In October 2011, *The Joplin Globe* released a hardcover pictorial book titled *32 Minutes in May: The Joplin Tornado*.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] On August 25, 2015, the historical fiction children's novel *I Survived the Joplin Tornado, 2011* by Lauren Tarshis was released.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] A number of documentaries have been produced about the Joplin tornado and its effects on the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] These include *Heartland: A Portrait of Survival*, directed by Erica Tremblay and featured at the Omaha Film Festival and the St.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Louis International Film Festival, as well as *Deadline in Disaster* (directed by Beth Pike), which followed the staff of The Joplin Globe in the tornado's aftermath and received a regional Emmy in the Documentary-Cultural category during the 37th Mid-America Emmy Awards.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] In March 2025, Netflix released a feature-length documentary on the tornado, titled *The Twister: Caught in the Storm*.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Residents of Joplin who recalled the storm were interviewed for the documentary.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-joplin-tornado] Every time the wind gets stronger, or the sirens go...
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 March 2011, at 14:46:24 JST (05:46:24 UTC), a Mw 9.0–9.1 undersea megathrust earthquake occurred in the Pacific Ocean, 72 km (45 mi) east of the Oshika Peninsula of the Tōhoku region of Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It lasted approximately six minutes and caused a tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is sometimes known in Japan as the "**Great East Japan Earthquake**" (東日本大震災, *Higashi Nihon Daishinsai*), among other names.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is often referred to by its numerical date, **3.11** (read *San ten Ichi-ichi* in Japanese).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was the most powerful ever recorded in Japan, and the fourth most powerful recorded in the world since modern seismography began in 1900.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It triggered powerful tsunami waves that may have reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture, and which, in the Sendai area, traveled at 700 km/h (435 mph) and up to 10 km (6 mi) inland.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents of Sendai had only eight to ten minutes of warning, and more than a hundred evacuation sites were washed away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The snowfall which accompanied the tsunami and the freezing temperature hindered rescue works; for instance, in Ishinomaki, the city with the most deaths, the temperature was 0 °C (32 °F) as the tsunami hit.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, 284 firefighters dead from attempts to close preventative fire gates, and 2,553 missing.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report in 2015 found that 228,863 people were still living away from their home either temporarily or permanently.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami caused the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster, primarily the meltdowns of three of its reactors, the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima and the associated evacuation zones affecting hundreds of thousands of residents.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Many electrical generators ran out of fuel.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The loss of electrical power halted cooling systems, causing heat to build.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Without ventilation, hydrogen gas accumulated within the upper refueling hall and exploded, forcefully ejecting the refueling hall's blast panels.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Residents within a 20 km (12 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant and a 10 km (6.2 mi) radius of the Fukushima Daini Nuclear Power Plant were evacuated.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Early estimates placed insured losses from the earthquake alone at US$14.5 to $34.6 billion.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Bank of Japan offered ¥15 trillion (US$183 billion) to the banking system on 14 March 2011 in an effort to normalize market conditions.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The estimated economic damage amounted to over $300 billion, making it the costliest natural disaster in history.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a 2020 study, "the earthquake and its aftermaths resulted in a 0.47 percentage point decline in Japan's real GDP growth in the year following the disaster".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake was initially reported as 7.9 Mw by the USGS before it was quickly upgraded to 8.8 Mw, then to 8.9 Mw, and then finally to 9.0 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 11 July 2016, the USGS further upgraded the earthquake to 9.1.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Sendai was the nearest major city to the earthquake, 130 km (81 mi) from the epicenter; the earthquake occurred 373 km (232 mi) northeast of Tokyo.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main earthquake was preceded by a number of large foreshocks, with hundreds of aftershocks reported.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One of the first major foreshocks was a 7.2 Mw event on 9 March, approximately 40 km (25 mi) from the epicenter of the 11 March earthquake, with another three on the same day in excess of 6.0 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the main earthquake on 11 March, a 7.4 Mw aftershock was reported at 15:08 JST (6:06 UTC), succeeded by a 7.9 Mw at 15:15 JST (6:16 UTC) and a 7.7 Mw at 15:26 JST (6:26 UTC).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Over 800 aftershocks of magnitude 4.5 Mw or greater occurred after the initial quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Aftershocks followed Omori's law, which states that the rate of aftershocks declines with the reciprocal of the time since the main quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The aftershocks thus tapered off over time, but continued for years after the initial quake, including one on 26 October 2013 (local time) of magnitude 7.1 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Initially, the earthquake caused part of Honshu's Pacific coast to sink by roughly a meter, but after about three years, the coast rose back and then kept on rising to exceed its original height.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This megathrust earthquake was a recurrence of the mechanism of the earlier 869 Sanriku earthquake, which has been estimated as having a magnitude of at least 8.4 Mw, which also created a large tsunami that inundated the Sendai plain.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three tsunami deposits have been identified within the Holocene sequence of the plain, all formed within the last 3,000 years, suggesting an 800 to 1,100 year recurrence interval for large tsunamigenic earthquakes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2001 it was reckoned that there was a high likelihood of a large tsunami hitting the Sendai plain as more than 1,100 years had then elapsed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In 2007, the probability of an earthquake with a magnitude of Mw 8.1–8.3 was estimated as 99% within the following 30 years.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This earthquake occurred where the Pacific plate is subducting under the plate beneath northern Honshu.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific plate, which moves at a rate of 8 to 9 cm (3.1 to 3.5 in) per year, dips under Honshu's underlying plate, building large amounts of elastic energy.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motion pushes the upper plate down until the accumulated stress causes a seismic slip-rupture event.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The break caused the sea floor to rise by several meters.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The magnitude of this earthquake was a surprise to some seismologists.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A quake of this magnitude usually has a rupture length of at least 500 km (310 mi) and generally requires a long, relatively straight fault surface.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because the plate boundary and subduction zone in the area of the Honshu rupture is not very straight, it is unusual for the magnitude of its earthquake to exceed 8.5 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The hypocentral region of this earthquake extended from offshore Iwate Prefecture to offshore Ibaraki Prefecture.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency said that the earthquake may have ruptured the fault zone from Iwate to Ibaraki with a length of 500 km (310 mi) and a width of 200 km (120 mi).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Analysis showed that this earthquake consisted of a set of three events.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other major earthquakes with tsunamis struck the Sanriku Coast region in 1896 and in 1933.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The source area of this earthquake has a relatively high coupling coefficient surrounded by areas of relatively low coupling coefficients in the west, north, and south.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment of this earthquake accounts for about 93% of the estimated cumulative moment from 1926 to March 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hence, earthquakes in this area with magnitudes of about 7 since 1926 had only released part of the accumulated energy.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the area near the trench, the coupling coefficient is high, which could act as the source of the large tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Most of the foreshocks are interplate earthquakes with thrust-type focal mechanisms.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Both interplate and intraplate earthquakes appeared in the aftershocks offshore Sanriku coast with considerable proportions.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surface energy of the seismic waves from the earthquake was calculated to be 1.9×1017 joules, which is nearly double that of the 9.1 Mw 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami that killed 230,000 people.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] If harnessed, the seismic energy from this earthquake would power a city the size of Los Angeles for an entire year.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The seismic moment (M0), which represents a physical size for the event, was calculated by the USGS at 3.9×1022 joules, slightly less than the 2004 Indian Ocean quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The strong ground motion registered at the maximum of *Shindo* 7 on the Japan Meteorological Agency seismic intensity scale in Kurihara, Miyagi Prefecture.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Three other prefectures—Fukushima, Ibaraki and Tochigi—recorded a 6 upper on the JMA scale.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seismic stations in Iwate, Gunma, Saitama and Chiba Prefectures measured a 6 lower, while Tokyo and five other prefectures recorded 5 upper.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan's National Research Institute for Earth Science and Disaster Prevention (NIED) calculated a peak ground acceleration of 2.99 *g* (29.33 m/s2).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Tremors from the earthquake were also felt in the Northern Mariana Islands, the Korean Peninsula, Taiwan, Northeast China and the Russian Far East.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Portions of northeastern Japan shifted by as much as 2.4 meters (7 ft 10 in) closer to North America, making some sections of Japan's landmass wider than before.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Those areas of Japan closest to the epicenter experienced the largest shifts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 400-kilometer (250 mi) stretch of coastline dropped vertically by 0.6 meters (2 ft 0 in), allowing the tsunami to travel farther and faster onto land.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One early estimate suggested that the Pacific plate may have moved westward by up to 20 meters (66 ft), and another early estimate put the amount of slippage at as much as 40 m (130 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 6 April, the Japanese coast guard said that the quake shifted the seabed near the epicenter 24 meters (79 ft) and elevated the seabed off the coast of Miyagi Prefecture by 3 meters (9.8 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A report by the Japan Agency for Marine-Earth Science and Technology, published in *Science* on 2 December 2011, concluded that the seabed in the area between the epicenter and the Japan Trench moved 50 meters (160 ft) east-southeast and rose about 7 meters (23 ft) as a result of the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The report also stated that the quake had caused several major landslides on the seabed in the affected area.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Earth's axis shifted by estimates of between 10 and 25 cm (4 and 10 in).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This deviation led to a number of small planetary changes, including the length of a day, the tilt of the Earth, and the Chandler wobble.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The speed of the Earth's rotation increased, shortening the day by 1.8 microseconds due to the redistribution of Earth's mass.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The axial shift was caused by the redistribution of mass on the Earth's surface, which changed the planet's moment of inertia.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because of conservation of angular momentum, such changes of inertia result in small changes to the Earth's rate of rotation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These are expected changes for an earthquake of this magnitude.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The earthquake also generated infrasound waves detected by perturbations in the orbit of the GOCE satellite, which thus serendipitously became the first seismograph in orbit.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Following the earthquake, cracks were observed to have formed in the roof of Mount Fuji's magma chamber.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Seiches observed in Sognefjorden, Norway, were attributed to distant S waves and Love waves generated by the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] These seiches began to occur roughly half an hour after the main shock hit Japan, and continued to occur for 3 hours, during which waves of up to 1.5 meters high were observed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Soil liquefaction was evident in areas of reclaimed land around Tokyo, particularly in Urayasu, Chiba City, Funabashi, Narashino (all in Chiba Prefecture) and in the Koto, Edogawa, Minato, Chūō, and Ōta wards of Tokyo.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Approximately 30 homes or buildings were destroyed and 1,046 other buildings were damaged to varying degrees.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Nearby Haneda Airport, built mostly on reclaimed land, was not damaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Odaiba also experienced liquefaction, but damage was minimal.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Shinmoedake, a volcano in Kyushu, erupted three days after the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The volcano had previously erupted in January 2011; it is not known if the later eruption was linked to the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Antarctica, the seismic waves from the earthquake were reported to have caused the Whillans Ice Stream to slip by about 0.5 meters (1 ft 8 in).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The first sign international researchers had that the earthquake caused such a dramatic change in the Earth's rotation came from the United States Geological Survey which monitors Global Positioning Satellite (GPS) stations across the world.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Survey team had several GPS monitors located near the scene of the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The GPS station located nearest the epicenter moved almost 4 m (13 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This motivated government researchers to look into other ways the earthquake may have had large scale effects on the planet.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Calculations at NASA's Jet Propulsion Laboratory determined that the Earth's rotation was changed by the earthquake to the point where the days are now 1.8 microseconds shorter.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Japan experienced over 1,000 aftershocks since the earthquake, with 80 registering over magnitude 6.0 Mw and several of which have been over magnitude 7.0 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A month later, a major aftershock struck offshore on 7 April with a magnitude of 7.1 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Its epicenter was underwater, 66 km (41 mi) off the coast of Sendai.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Japan Meteorological Agency assigned a magnitude of 7.4 MJMA, while the United States Geological Survey lowered it to 7.1 Mw.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least four people were killed, and electricity was cut off across much of northern Japan including the loss of external power to Higashidōri Nuclear Power Plant and Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Four days later on 11 April, another magnitude 7.1 Mw aftershock struck Fukushima, causing additional damage and killing a total of three people.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 7 December 2012 a large aftershock of magnitude 7.3 Mw caused a minor tsunami, and again on 26 October 2013 a small tsunami was recorded after a 7.1 Mw aftershock.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 16 March 2012 aftershocks continued, totaling 1887 events over magnitude 4.0; a regularly updated map showing all shocks of magnitude 4.5 and above near or off the east coast of Honshu in the last seven days showed over 20 events.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of 11 March 2016 there had been 869 aftershocks of 5.0 Mw or greater, 118 of 6.0 Mw or greater, and 9 over 7.0 Mw as reported by the Japan Meteorological Agency.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The number of aftershocks was associated with decreased health across Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 February 2021, a magnitude 7.1–7.3 earthquake struck off the coast of Sendai.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It caused some damage in Miyagi and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One person was killed, and 185 were injured.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Geospatial Information Authority of Japan reported land subsidence based on the height of triangulation stations in the area measured by GPS as compared to their previous values from 14 April 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Scientists say that the subsidence is permanent.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As a result, the communities in question are now more susceptible to flooding during high tides.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] One minute before the earthquake was felt in Tokyo, the Earthquake Early Warning system, which includes more than 1,000 seismometers in Japan, sent out warnings of impending strong shaking to millions.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It is believed that the early warning by the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) saved many lives.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning for the general public was delivered about eight seconds after the first P wave was detected, or about 31 seconds after the earthquake occurred.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the estimated intensities were smaller than the actual ones in some places, especially in Kanto, Koshinetsu, and Northern Tōhoku regions where the populace warning did not trigger.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There were also cases where large differences between estimated intensities by the Earthquake Early Warning system and the actual intensities occurred in the aftershocks and triggered earthquakes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Such discrepancies in the warning were attributed by the JMA to the system's inability to distinguish between two different earthquakes that happened at around same time, as well as to the reduced number of reporting seismometers due to power outages and connection failures.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The system's software was subsequently modified to handle this kind of situation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] An upthrust of 6 to 8 meters (20 to 26 ft) along a 180-kilometer (110 mi)-wide seabed at 60 kilometers (37 mi) offshore from the east coast of Tōhoku resulted in a major tsunami that brought destruction along the Pacific coastline of Japan's northern islands.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Thousands of people died and entire towns were devastated.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami propagated throughout the Pacific Ocean region reaching the entire Pacific coast of North and South America from Alaska to Chile.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Warnings were issued and evacuations were carried out in many countries bordering the Pacific.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Although the tsunami affected many of these places, the heights of the waves were minor.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Chile's Pacific coast, one of the farthest from Japan at about 17,000 kilometers (11,000 mi) away, was struck by waves 2 meters (6.6 ft) high, compared with an estimated wave height of 38.9 meters (128 ft) at Omoe peninsula, Miyako city, Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami warning issued by the Japan Meteorological Agency was the most serious on its warning scale; it was rated as a "major tsunami", being at least 3 meters (9.8 ft) high.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The actual height prediction varied, the greatest being for Miyagi at 6 meters (20 ft) high.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami inundated a total area of approximately 561 square kilometers (217 sq mi) in Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 15:55 JST, a tsunami was observed flooding Sendai Airport, which is located near the coast of Miyagi Prefecture, with waves sweeping away cars and planes and flooding various buildings as they traveled inland.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The impact of the tsunami in and around Sendai Airport was filmed by an NHK News helicopter, showing a number of vehicles on local roads trying to escape the approaching wave and being engulfed by it.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 4-meter-high (13 ft) tsunami hit Iwate Prefecture.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Wakabayashi Ward in Sendai was also particularly hard hit.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At least 101 designated tsunami evacuation sites were hit by the wave.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Like the 2004 Indian Ocean earthquake and tsunami, the damage by surging water, though much more localized, was far more deadly and destructive than the actual quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Entire towns were destroyed in tsunami-hit areas in Japan, including 9,500 missing in Minamisanriku; one thousand bodies had been recovered in the town by 14 March 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Among the factors in the high death toll was the unexpectedly large water surge.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The sea walls in several cities had been built to protect against tsunamis of much lower heights.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, many people caught in the tsunami thought they were on high enough ground to be safe.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] According to a special committee on disaster prevention designated by the Japanese government, the tsunami protection policy had been intended to deal with only tsunamis that had been scientifically proved to occur repeatedly.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The committee advised that future policy should be to protect against the highest possible tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Because tsunami walls had been overtopped, the committee also suggested, besides building taller tsunami walls, also teaching citizens how to evacuate if a large-scale tsunami should strike.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Large parts of Kuji and the southern section of Ōfunato including the port area were almost entirely destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also largely destroyed was Rikuzentakata, where the tsunami was three stories high.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Other cities destroyed or heavily damaged by the tsunami include Kamaishi, Miyako, Ōtsuchi, and Yamada (in Iwate Prefecture), Namie, Sōma, and Minamisōma (in Fukushima Prefecture) and Shichigahama, Higashimatsushima, Onagawa, Natori, Ishinomaki, and Kesennuma (in Miyagi Prefecture).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The most severe effects of the tsunami were felt along a 670-kilometer-long (420 mi) stretch of coastline from Erimo, Hokkaido, in the north to Ōarai, Ibaraki, in the south, with most of the destruction in that area occurring in the hour following the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Near Ōarai, people captured images of a huge whirlpool that had been generated by the tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami washed away the sole bridge to Miyatojima, Miyagi, isolating the island's 900 residents.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2 meters (6 ft 7 in) high tsunami hit Chiba Prefecture about 2+1⁄2 hours after the quake, causing heavy damage to cities such as Asahi.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On 13 March 2011, the Japan Meteorological Agency (JMA) published details of tsunami observations recorded around the coastline of Japan following the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The bulletin also included initial tsunami observation details, as well as more detailed maps for the coastlines affected by the tsunami waves.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami at Ryōri Bay (綾里湾), Ōfunato reached a height of 40.1 meters (132 ft) (run-up elevation).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Fishing equipment was scattered on the high cliff above the bay.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At Tarō, Iwate, the tsunami reached a height of 37.9 meters (124 ft) up the slope of a mountain some 200 meters (660 ft) away from the coastline.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, at the slope of a nearby mountain from 400 meters (1,300 ft) away at Aneyoshi fishery port (姉吉漁港) of Omoe peninsula (重茂半島) in Miyako, Iwate, Tokyo University of Marine Science and Technology found estimated tsunami run up height of 38.9 meters (128 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This height is deemed the record in Japan historically, as of reporting date, that exceeds 38.2 meters (125 ft) from the 1896 Sanriku earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was also estimated that the tsunami reached heights of up to 40.5 meters (133 ft) in Miyako in Tōhoku's Iwate Prefecture.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The inundated areas closely matched those of the 869 Sanriku tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Inundation heights were observed along 2,000 kilometers (1,200 mi) of the coast from Hokkaido to Kyushu in a 2012 study.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Maximum run-up heights greater than 10 meters (33 ft) were distributed along 530 kilometers (330 mi) of coast, and maximum run-up heights greater than 20 meters (66 ft) were distributed along 200 kilometers (120 mi) of the coast, measured directly.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami resulted in significant erosion of the Rikuzen-Takata coastline, mainly caused by backwash.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A 2016 study indicated that the coast has not naturally recovered at a desirable rate since the tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A Japanese government study found that 58% of people in coastal areas in Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures heeded tsunami warnings immediately after the quake and headed for higher ground.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who attempted to evacuate after hearing the warning, only five percent were caught in the tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Of those who did not heed the warning, 49% were hit by the water.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Delayed evacuations in response to the warnings had a number of causes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami height that had been initially predicted by the tsunami warning system was lower than the actual tsunami height; this error contributed to the delayed escape of some residents.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The discrepancy arose as follows: in order to produce a quick prediction of a tsunami's height and thus to provide a timely warning, the initial earthquake and tsunami warning that was issued for the event was based on a calculation that requires only about three minutes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This calculation is, in turn, based on the maximum amplitude of the seismic wave.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The amplitude of the seismic wave is measured using the JMA magnitude scale, which is similar to Richter scale.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, these scales "saturate" for earthquakes that are above a certain magnitude (magnitude 8 on the JMA scale); that is, in the case of very large earthquakes, the scales' values change little despite large differences in the earthquakes' energy.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] This resulted in an underestimation of the tsunami's height in initial reports.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Problems in issuing updates also contributed to delays in evacuations.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The warning system was supposed to be updated about 15 minutes after the earthquake occurred, by which time the calculation for the moment magnitude scale would normally be completed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, the strong quake had exceeded the measurement limit of all of the teleseismometers within Japan, and thus it was impossible to calculate the moment magnitude based on data from those seismometers.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Another cause of delayed evacuations was the release of the second update on the tsunami warning long after the earthquake (28 minutes, according to observations); by that time, power failures and similar circumstances reportedly prevented the update from reaching some residents.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Also, observed data from tidal meters that were located off the coast were not fully reflected in the second warning.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In response to the aforementioned shortcomings in the tsunami warning system, JMA began an investigation in 2011 and updated their system in 2013.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the updated system, for a powerful earthquake that is capable of causing the JMA magnitude scale to saturate, no quantitative prediction will be released in the initial warning; instead, there will be words that describe the situation's emergency.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There are plans to install new teleseismometers with the ability to measure larger earthquakes, which would allow the calculation of a quake's moment magnitude scale in a timely manner.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] JMA also implemented a simpler empirical method to integrate, into a tsunami warning, data from GPS tidal meters as well as from undersea water pressure meters, and there are plans to install more of these meters and to develop further technology to utilize data observed by them.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] To prevent under-reporting of tsunami heights, early quantitative observation data that are smaller than the expected amplitude will be overridden and the public will instead be told that the situation is under observation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] About 90 seconds after an earthquake, an additional report on the possibility of a tsunami will also be included in observation reports, in order to warn people before the JMA magnitude can be calculated.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The Pacific Tsunami Warning Center (PTWC) in Hawaii issued tsunami watches and announcements for locations in the Pacific.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] At 07:30 UTC, PTWC issued a widespread tsunami warning covering the entire Pacific Ocean.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Russia evacuated 11,000 residents from coastal areas of the Kuril Islands.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The United States National Tsunami Warning Center issued a tsunami warning for the coastal areas in most of California, all of Oregon, and the western part of Alaska, and a tsunami advisory covering the Pacific coastlines of most of Alaska, and all of Washington and British Columbia, Canada.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In California and Oregon, up to 2.4 m-high (7.9 ft) tsunami waves hit some areas, damaging docks and harbors and causing over US$10 million in damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In Curry County, Oregon, US$7 million in damage occurred including the destruction of 1,100 m (3,600 ft) of docks at the Brookings harbor; the county received over US$1 million in FEMA emergency grants from the US Federal Government.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Surges of up to 1 m (3 ft 3 in) hit Vancouver Island in Canada prompting some evacuations, and causing boats to be banned from the waters surrounding the island for 12 hours following the wave strike, leaving many island residents in the area without means of getting to work.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Philippines, waves up to 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) high hit the eastern seaboard of the country.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some houses along the coast in Jayapura, Indonesia were destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Authorities in Wewak, East Sepik, Papua New Guinea evacuated 100 patients from the city's Boram Hospital before it was hit by waves, causing an estimated US$4 million in damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Hawaii estimated damage to public infrastructure alone at US$3 million, with damage to private properties, including resort hotels such as Four Seasons Resort Hualalai, estimated at tens of millions of dollars.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] It was reported that a 1.5 m-high (4.9 ft) wave completely submerged Midway Atoll's reef inlets and Spit Island, killing more than 110,000 nesting seabirds at the Midway Atoll National Wildlife Refuge.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Some other South Pacific countries, including Tonga and New Zealand, and US territories American Samoa and Guam, experienced larger-than-normal waves, but did not report any major damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] However, in Guam some roads were closed off and people were evacuated from low-lying areas.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Along the Pacific Coast of Mexico and South America, tsunami surges were reported, but in most places caused little or no damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] Peru reported a wave of 1.5 m (4 ft 11 in) and more than 300 homes damaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The surge in Chile was large enough to damage more than 200 houses, with waves of up to 3 m (9.8 ft).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] In the Galápagos Islands, 260 families received assistance following a 3 m (9.8 ft) surge which arrived 20 hours after the earthquake, after the tsunami warning had been lifted.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] There was a great deal of damage to buildings on the islands and one man was injured but there were no reported fatalities.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The tsunami broke icebergs off the Sulzberger Ice Shelf in Antarctica, 13,000 km (8,100 mi) away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] The main iceberg measured 9.5 km × 6.5 km (5.9 mi × 4.0 mi) (approximately the area of Manhattan Island) and about 80 m (260 ft) thick.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] A total of 125 km2 (48 sq mi; 31,000 acres) of ice broke away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] As of April 2012, wreckage from the tsunami spread around the world, including a soccer ball which was found in Alaska's Middleton Island and a Japanese motorcycle found in British Columbia, Canada.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] On the day of the earthquake, the waters of several fjords across Norway appeared to seethe as if boiling, and formed waves that rolled onto shores, most prominently in Sognefjorden, where the phenomenon was caught on film.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p01] After two years of research into the incidents in Norway, scientists concluded that the seismic energy of the earthquake generated seiche waves thousands of kilometers away.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The official figures released in 2021 reported 19,759 deaths, 6,242 injured, and 2,553 missing.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were 10,567 deaths in Miyagi, 5,145 in Iwate, 3,920 in Fukushima, 66 in Ibaraki, 22 in Chiba, eight in Tokyo, six in Kanagawa, four in Tochigi, three each in Aomori and Yamagata, and one each in Gunma, Saitama and Hokkaido.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The leading causes of death were drowning (90.64% or 14,308 bodies), burning (0.9% or 145 bodies) and others (4.2% or 667 bodies, mostly crushed by heavy objects).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Injuries related to nuclear exposure or the discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima are difficult to trace as 60% of the 20,000 workers on-site declined to participate in state-sponsored free health checks.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Elderly aged over 60 account for 65.8% of all deaths, as shown on the table to the right.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A few cases of suicide are also included.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred during the first six months after the earthquake and the number dropped thereafter, but as time has passed, the number has continued to increase.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most of these deaths occurred in Fukushima Prefecture, where the prefectural government has suggested that they could be due to evacuations caused by the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Fukushima Prefecture, these indirect casualties have already resulted in more deaths than the number of people killed directly by earthquake and tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Save the Children reports that as many as 100,000 children were uprooted from their homes, some of whom were separated from their families because the earthquake occurred during the school day.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 236 children were orphaned in the prefectures of Iwate, Miyagi and Fukushima by the disaster; 1,580 children lost either one or both parents, 846 in Miyagi, 572 in Iwate, and 162 in Fukushima.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The quake and tsunami killed 378 elementary, middle-school, and high school students and left 158 others missing.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One elementary school in Ishinomaki, Miyagi, Okawa Elementary School, lost 74 of 108 students and 10 of 13 teachers in the tsunami due to poor decision making in evacuation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Japanese Foreign Ministry confirmed the deaths of nineteen foreigners.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Among them were two English teachers from the United States affiliated with the Japan Exchange and Teaching Program; a Canadian missionary in Shiogama; and citizens of China, North and South Korea, Taiwan, Pakistan and the Philippines.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 9:30 UTC on 11 March 2011, Google Person Finder, which was previously used in the Haitian, Chilean, and Christchurch, New Zealand earthquakes, was collecting information about survivors and their locations.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese funerals are normally elaborate Buddhist ceremonies that entail cremation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The thousands of bodies, however, exceeded the capacity of available crematoriums and morgues, many of them damaged, and there were shortages of both kerosene—each cremation requires 50 litres—and dry ice for preservation.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The single crematorium in Higashimatsushima, for example, could only handle four bodies a day, although hundreds were found there.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Governments and the military were forced to bury many bodies in hastily dug mass graves with rudimentary or no rites, although relatives of the deceased were promised that they would be cremated later.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 27 May 2011, three Japan Ground Self-Defense Force members had died while conducting relief operations in Tōhoku.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of March 2012, the Japanese government had recognized 1,331 deaths as indirectly related to the earthquake, such as caused by harsh living conditions after the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of 30 April 2012, 18 people had died and 420 had been injured while participating in disaster recovery or clean-up efforts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami was reported to have caused several deaths outside Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] One man was killed in Jayapura, Papua, Indonesia after being swept out to sea.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A man who is said to have been attempting to photograph the oncoming tsunami at the mouth of the Klamath River, south of Crescent City, California, was swept out to sea.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] His body was found on 2 April 2011 along Ocean Beach in Fort Stevens State Park, Oregon, 530 km (330 mi) to the north.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The degree and extent of damage caused by the earthquake and resulting tsunami were enormous, with most of the damage being caused by the tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Video footage of the towns that were worst affected shows little more than piles of rubble, with almost no parts of any structures left standing.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Estimates of the cost of the damage range well into the tens of billions of US dollars; before-and-after satellite photographs of devastated regions show immense damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Although Japan has invested the equivalent of billions of dollars on anti-tsunami seawalls which line at least 40% of its 34,751 km (21,593 mi) coastline and stand up to 12 m (39 ft) high, the tsunami simply washed over the top of some seawalls, collapsing some in the process.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's National Police Agency said on 3 April 2011, that 45,700 buildings were destroyed and 144,300 were damaged by the quake and tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The damaged buildings included 29,500 structures in Miyagi Prefecture, 12,500 in Iwate Prefecture and 2,400 in Fukushima Prefecture.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Three hundred hospitals with 20 beds or more in Tōhoku were damaged by the disaster, with 11 being completely destroyed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami created an estimated 24–25 million tons of rubble and debris in Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the National Police Agency of Japan on 10 September 2018 listed 121,778 buildings as "total collapsed", with a further 280,926 buildings "half collapsed", and another 699,180 buildings "partially damaged".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The earthquake and tsunami also caused extensive and severe structural damage in north-eastern Japan, including heavy damage to roads and railways as well as fires in many areas, and a dam collapse.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japanese Prime Minister Naoto Kan said, "In the 65 years after the end of World War II, this is the toughest and the most difficult crisis for Japan." Around 4.4 million households in northeastern Japan were left without electricity and 1.5 million without water.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An estimated 230,000 automobiles and trucks were damaged or destroyed in the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As of the end of May 2011, residents of Iwate, Miyagi, and Fukushima prefectures had requested the deregistration of 15,000 vehicles, meaning that the owners of those vehicles were writing them off as unrepairable or unsalvageable.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Low temperature and snowfall were major concerns after the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Snow arrived minutes before or after the tsunami, depending on locations.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki, the city which suffered the most deaths, a temperature of 0 °C (32 °F) was measured, and it began to snow within a couple of hours of the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major snow fell again on 16 March, and intermittently in the coming weeks.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] 18 March was the coldest of that month, recording −4 to 6 °C (25 to 43 °F) in Sendai.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Photos of city ruins covered with snow were featured in various photo albums in international media, including NASA.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami produced huge amounts of debris: estimates of 5 million tonnes of waste were reported by the Japanese Ministry of the Environment.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Some of this waste, mostly plastic and styrofoam, washed up on the coasts of Canada and the United States in late 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Along the west coast of the United States, this increased the amount of litter by a factor of ten and may have transported alien species.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All of Japan's ports were briefly shut down after the earthquake, though the ones in Tokyo and southwards soon re-opened.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Fifteen ports were located in the disaster zone.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The north eastern ports of Hachinohe, Sendai, Ishinomaki and Onahama were destroyed, while the Port of Chiba (which serves the hydrocarbon industry) and Japan's ninth-largest container port at Kashima were also affected, though less severely.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The ports at Hitachinaka, Hitachi, Soma, Shiogama, Kesennuma, Ofunato, Kamashi and Miyako were also damaged and closed to ships.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All 15 ports reopened to limited ship traffic by 29 March 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A total of 319 fishing ports, about 10% of Japan's fishing ports, were damaged in the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most were restored to operating condition by 18 April 2012.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Port of Tokyo suffered slight damage; the effects of the quake included visible smoke rising from a building in the port with parts of the port areas being flooded, including soil liquefaction in Tokyo Disneyland's parking lot.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fujinuma irrigation dam in Sukagawa ruptured, causing flooding and the washing away of five homes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eight people were missing and four bodies were discovered by the morning.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Reportedly, some locals had attempted to repair leaks in the dam before it completely failed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 12 March 252 dams were inspected and it was discovered that six embankment dams had shallow cracks on their crests.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reservoir at one concrete gravity dam suffered a small non-serious slope failure.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All damaged dams are functioning with no problems.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four dams within the quake area were unreachable.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the immediate aftermath of the calamity, at least 1.5 million households were reported to have lost access to water supplies.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, this number fell to 1.04 million.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] According to the Japanese trade ministry, around 4.4 million households served by Tōhoku Electric Power (TEP) in northeastern Japan were left without electricity.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Several nuclear and conventional power plants went offline, reducing the Tokyo Electric Power Company's (TEPCO) total capacity by 21 GW.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts began on 14 March due to power shortages caused by the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] TEPCO, which normally provides approximately 40 GW of electricity, announced that it could only provide about 30 GW, because 40% of the electricity used in the greater Tokyo area was supplied by reactors in the Niigata and Fukushima prefectures.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reactors at the Fukushima Daiichi and Fukushima Dai-ni plants were automatically taken offline when the first earthquake occurred and sustained major damage from the earthquake and subsequent tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Rolling blackouts of approximately three hours were experienced throughout April and May while TEPCO scrambled to find a temporary power solution.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blackouts affected Tokyo, Kanagawa, Eastern Shizuoka, Yamanashi, Chiba, Ibaraki, Saitama, Tochigi, and Gunma prefectures.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Voluntary reductions in electricity use by consumers in the Kanto area helped reduce the predicted frequency and duration of the blackouts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] By 21 March 2011, the number of households in the north without electricity fell to 242,927.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power was not able to provide the Kanto region with additional power because TEP's power plants were also damaged in the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Two substations, one in Shizuoka Prefecture and one in Nagano Prefecture, were able to convert between frequencies and transfer electricity from Kansai to Kanto and Tōhoku, but their capacity was limited to 1 GW.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] With damage to so many power plants, it was feared it might be years before a long-term solution could be found.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To help alleviate the shortage, three steel manufacturers in the Kanto region contributed electricity produced by their in-house conventional power stations to TEPCO for distribution to the general public.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Sumitomo Metal Industries could produce up to 500 MW, JFE Steel 400 MW, and Nippon Steel 500 MW of electric power.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Auto and auto parts makers in Kanto and Tōhoku agreed in May 2011 to operate their factories on Saturdays and Sundays and close on Thursdays and Fridays to help alleviate electricity shortages during the summer of 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The public and other companies were also encouraged to conserve electricity in the 2011 summer months (Setsuden).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expected electricity crisis in 2011 summer was successfully prevented thanks to all the *setsuden* measures.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Peak electricity consumption recorded by TEPCO during the period was 49.22GW, which is 10.77GW (18%) lower than the peak consumption in the previous year.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Overall electricity consumption during July and August was also 14% less than in the previous year.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The peak electricity consumption within TEP's area was 12.46GW during the 2011 summer, 3.11GW (20%) less than the peak consumption in the previous year, and the overall consumption have been reduced by 11% in July with 17% in August compared to previous year.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A 220,000-barrel-per-day (35,000 m3) oil refinery of Cosmo Oil Company was set on fire by the quake at Ichihara, Chiba Prefecture, to the east of Tokyo.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] It was extinguished after ten days, injuring six people, and destroying storage tanks.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Other refineries halted production due to safety checks and power loss.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Sendai, a 145,000-barrel-per-day (23,100 m3) refinery owned by the largest refiner in Japan, JX Nippon Oil & Energy, was also set ablaze by the quake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Workers were evacuated, but tsunami warnings hindered efforts to extinguish the fire until 14 March, when officials planned to do so.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An analyst estimated that consumption of various types of oil could have increased by as much as 300,000 barrels (48,000 m3) per day (as well as LNG), as back-up power plants burning fossil fuels attempted to compensate for the loss of 11 GW of Japan's nuclear power capacity.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The city-owned plant for importing liquefied natural gas in Sendai was severely damaged, and supplies were halted for at least a month.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In addition to refining and storage, several power plants were damaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] These include Sendai #4, New-Sendai #1 and #2, Haranomachi #1 and #2, Hirono #2 and #4 and Hitachinaka #1.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Fukushima Daiichi, Fukushima Daini, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant and Tōkai nuclear power stations, consisting of a total eleven reactors, were automatically shut down following the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Higashidōri, also on the northeast coast, was already shut down for a periodic inspection.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cooling is needed to remove decay heat after a Generation II reactor has been shut down, and to maintain spent fuel pools.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The backup cooling process is powered by emergency diesel generators at the plants and at Rokkasho nuclear reprocessing plant.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] At Fukushima Daiichi and Daini, tsunami waves overtopped seawalls and destroyed diesel backup power systems, leading to severe problems at Fukushima Daiichi, including three large explosions and radioactive leakage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Subsequent analysis found that many Japanese nuclear plants, including Fukushima Daiichi, were not adequately protected against tsunamis.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water in Fukushima was confirmed in later analysis at the three reactors at Fukushima I (Units 1, 2, and 3), which suffered meltdowns and continued to leak coolant water.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftershock on 7 April caused the loss of external power to Rokkasho Reprocessing Plant and Higashidori Nuclear Power Plant but backup generators were functional.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of its four external power lines and temporarily lost cooling function in its spent fuel pools for "20 to 80 minutes".
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of "up to 3.8 litres [1.0 US gal]" of radioactive water also occurred at Onagawa following the aftershock.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A report by the IAEA in 2012 found that the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant had remained largely undamaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2013, only two nuclear reactors in Japan had been restarted since the 2011 shutdowns.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2019, there were 42 operable reactors in Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Of these, only nine reactors in five power plants were operating after having been restarted post-2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan declared a state of emergency following the failure of the cooling system at the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant, resulting in the evacuation of nearby residents.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Officials from the Japanese Nuclear and Industrial Safety Agency reported that radiation levels inside the plant were up to 1,000 times normal levels, and that radiation levels outside the plant were up to eight times normal levels.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Later, a state of emergency was also declared at the Fukushima Daini nuclear power plant about 11 km (6.8 mi) south.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Experts described the Fukushima disaster was not as bad as the Chernobyl disaster, but worse than the Three Mile Island accident.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The discharge of radioactive water of the Fukushima Daiichi Nuclear Power Plant was later detected in tap water.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive iodine was detected in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi, Gunma, Tokyo, Chiba, Saitama, and Niigata, and radioactive caesium in the tap water in Fukushima, Tochigi and Gunma.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive caesium, iodine, and strontium were also detected in the soil in some places in Fukushima.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There may be a need to replace the contaminated soil.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many radioactive hotspots were found outside the evacuation zone, including Tokyo.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Radioactive contamination of food products were detected in several places in Japan.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In 2021, the Japanese cabinet finally approved the dumping of radioactive water in Fukushima into the Pacific Ocean over a course of 30 years, with full support of IAEA.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] To this day, the water is still actively being de-contaminated and is scheduled to be completed by the year 2051.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A fire occurred in the turbine section of the Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant following the earthquake.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The blaze was in a building housing the turbine, which is sited separately from the plant's reactor, and was soon extinguished.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The plant was shut down as a precaution.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On 13 March the lowest-level state of emergency was declared regarding the Onagawa plant as radioactivity readings temporarily exceeded allowed levels in the area of the plant.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tōhoku Electric Power Co. stated this may have been due to radiation from the Fukushima Daiichi nuclear accidents but was not from the Onagawa plant itself.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] As a result of the 7 April aftershock, Onagawa Nuclear Power Plant lost three of four external power lines and lost cooling function for as much as 80 minutes.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A spill of a couple of litres of radioactive water occurred at Onagawa.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The number 2 reactor at Tōkai Nuclear Power Plant was shut down automatically.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Japan's transport network suffered severe disruptions.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Many sections of Tōhoku Expressway serving northern Japan were damaged.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The expressway did not reopen to general public use until 24 March 2011.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] All railway services were suspended in Tokyo, with an estimated 20,000 people stranded at major stations across the city.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In the hours after the earthquake, some train services were resumed.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Most Tokyo area train lines resumed full service by the next day—12 March.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twenty thousand stranded visitors spent the night of 11–12 March inside Tokyo Disneyland.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] A tsunami flooded Sendai Airport at 15:55 JST, about one hour after the initial quake, causing severe damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Narita and Haneda Airport both briefly suspended operations after the quake, but suffered little damage and reopened within 24 hours.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Eleven airliners bound for Narita were diverted to nearby Yokota Air Base.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Various train services around Japan were also canceled, with JR East suspending all services for the rest of the day.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Four trains on coastal lines were reported as being out of contact with operators; one, a four-car train on the Senseki Line, was found to have derailed, and its occupants were rescued shortly after 8 am the next morning.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There were no derailments of Shinkansen bullet train services in and out of Tokyo, but their services were also suspended.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tokaido Shinkansen resumed limited service late in the day and was back to its normal schedule by the next day, while the Jōetsu and Nagano Shinkansen resumed services late on 12 March.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Yamagata Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 31 March.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Derailments were minimized because of an early warning system that detected the earthquake before it struck.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The system automatically stopped all high-speed trains, which minimized the damage.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The Tōhoku Shinkansen line was worst hit, with JR East estimating that 1,100 sections of the line, varying from collapsed station roofs to bent power pylons, would need repairs.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on the Tōhoku Shinkansen partially resumed only in Kantō area on 15 March, with one round-trip service per hour between Tokyo and Nasu-Shiobara, and Tōhoku area service partially resumed on 22 March between Morioka and Shin-Aomori.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Services on Akita Shinkansen resumed with limited numbers of trains on 18 March.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Service between Tokyo and Shin-Aomori was restored by May, but at lower speeds due to ongoing restoration work; the pre-earthquake timetable was not reinstated until late September.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The rolling blackouts brought on by the crises at the nuclear power plants in Fukushima had a profound effect on the rail networks around Tokyo starting on 14 March.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Major railways began running trains at 10–20 minute intervals, rather than the usual 3–5 minute intervals, operating some lines only at rush hour and completely shutting down others; notably, the Tōkaidō Main Line, Yokosuka Line, Sōbu Main Line and Chūō-Sōbu Line were all stopped for the day.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] This led to near-paralysis within the capital, with long lines at train stations and many people unable to come to work or get home.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Railway operators gradually increased capacity over the next few days, until running at approximately 80% capacity by 17 March and relieving the worst of the passenger congestion.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] (left) and a damaged utility pole in Ishinomaki (right).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Cellular and landline phone service suffered major disruptions in the affected area.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Immediately after the earthquake cellular communication was jammed across much of Japan due to a surge of network activity.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] On the day of the quake itself American broadcaster NPR was unable to reach anyone in Sendai with a working phone or access to the Internet.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Internet services were largely unaffected in areas where basic infrastructure remained, despite the earthquake having damaged portions of several undersea cable systems landing in the affected regions; these systems were able to reroute around affected segments onto redundant links.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Within Japan, only a few websites were initially unreachable.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no loss of life, although the tsunami resulted in damage to all 18 Mitsubishi F-2 fighter jets of the 21st Fighter Training Squadron.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Twelve of the aircraft were scrapped, while the remaining six were slated for repair at a cost of 80 billion yen ($1 billion), exceeding the original cost of the aircraft.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] After the tsunami, elements of the Japan Maritime Self-Defense Force put to sea without orders and started rescuing those who had been washed out to sea.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Tsunami plans were for the Japan Self-Defense Forces assets to be led, directed, and coordinated by local civic governments.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] However, the earthquake destroyed town halls (the seat of local municipal government), police, and fire services in many places, so the military not only had to respond to but also command rescues.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Stone monuments at the UNESCO World Heritage Site: Shrines and Temples of Nikkō were toppled.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Tokyo, there was damage to Koishikawa Kōrakuen, Rikugien, Hamarikyū Onshi Teien, and the walls of Edo Castle.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Information on the condition of collections held by museums, libraries and archives is still incomplete.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] There was no damage to the Historic Monuments and Sites of Hiraizumi in Iwate Prefecture, and the recommendation for their inscription on the UNESCO World Heritage List in June was seized upon as a symbol of international recognition and recovery.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the earthquake and tsunami included a humanitarian crisis and a major economic impact.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The tsunami resulted in over 340,000 displaced people in the Tōhoku region, and shortages of food, water, shelter, medicine, and fuel for survivors.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In response, the Japanese government mobilized the Self-Defense Forces (under Joint Task Force – Tōhoku, led by Lieutenant General Eiji Kimizuka), while many countries sent search and rescue teams to help search for survivors.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Aid organizations in Japan and worldwide responded, with the Japanese Red Cross reporting $1 billion in donations.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The economic impact included immediate problems, with industrial production suspended in many factories, and the longer term issue of the cost of rebuilding, which has been estimated at ¥10 trillion ($122 billion).
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In comparison to the 1995 Great Hanshin earthquake, the East Japan earthquake brought serious damage to an extremely wide range.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The aftermath of the twin disasters left Japan's coastal cities and towns with nearly 25 million tons of debris.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In Ishinomaki alone, there were 17 trash collection sites 180 meters (590 ft) long and at least 4.5 meters (15 ft) high.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] An official in the city's government trash disposal department estimated that it would take three years to empty these sites.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In April 2015, authorities off the coast of Oregon discovered debris that was thought to be from a boat destroyed during the tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The cargo contained yellowtail amberjack, a species of fish that lives off the coast of Japan, still alive.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] KGW estimates that more than 1 million tons of debris still remain in the Pacific Ocean.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] In February 2016, a memorial was inaugurated by two architects for the victims of the disaster, consisting of a 6.5-square-metre (70 sq ft) structure on a hillside between a temple and a cherry tree in Ishinomaki.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] The reconstruction of the Tohoku coast was funded and piloted by the Japanese government.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p02] Structural adaptation to tsunamis was largely based on building higher seawalls, although seawalls proved largely ineffective in 2011, and the new seawalls would also not have been high enough.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Seismologists anticipated a very large quake would strike in the same place as the 1923 Great Kantō earthquake—in the Sagami Trough, southwest of Tokyo.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japanese government had tracked plate movements since 1976 in preparation for the so-called Tokai earthquake, predicted to take place in that region.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] However, occurring as it did 373 km (232 mi) north east of Tokyo, the Tōhoku earthquake came as a surprise to seismologists.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] While the Japan Trench was known for creating large quakes, it had not been expected to generate quakes above an 8.0 magnitude.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Also, a tsunami-earthquake with a tsunami magnitude scales (Mt) between 8.6 and 9.0 (Similar to the 1896 Sanriku earthquake, the Mt for the 2011 Tōhoku earthquake was 9.1–9.4) had a 30% chance to occur within 30 years.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The quake gave scientists the opportunity to collect a large amount of data to model the seismic events that took place in great detail.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] This data is expected to be used in a variety of ways, providing unprecedented information about how buildings respond to shaking, and other effects.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Gravimetric data from the quake have been used to create a model for increased warning time compared to seismic models, as gravity fields travel faster than seismic waves.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Researchers have also analysed the economic effects of this earthquake and have developed models of the nationwide propagation via interfirm supply networks of the shock that originated in the Tōhoku region.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] After the full extent of the disaster was known, researchers soon launched a project to gather all digital material relating to the disaster into an online searchable archive to form the basis of future research into the events during and after the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Disasters Digital Archive is presented in English and Japanese and is hosted at the Reischauer Institute of Japanese Studies at Harvard University in Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Some of the first research to come from the archive was a 2014 paper from the Digital Methods Initiative in Amsterdam about patterns of Twitter usage around the time of the disaster.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] At this time Japan's Disaster Management Office (Naikakufu Bosai Keikaku) published a bi-lingual guide in Japanese and English, *Disaster Management in Japan*, to outline the several varieties of natural disaster and the preparations being made for the eventuality of each.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The Japan Trench Fast Drilling Project, a scientific expedition conducted in 2012–2013, drilled ocean-floor boreholes through the fault zone of the earthquake and gathered important data about the rupture mechanism and physical properties of the fault that caused the 2011 earthquake and tsunami.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The 2011 Tōhoku earthquake and tsunami had a great environmental impact on Japan's eastern coast.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The rarity and magnitude of the earthquake-tsunami prompted researchers Jotaro Urabe, Takao Suzuki, Tatsuki Nishita, and Wataru Makino to study their immediate ecological impacts on intertidal flat communities at Sendai Bay and the Sanriku Ria coast.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Pre- and post-event surveys show a reduction in animal taxon richness and change in taxon composition mainly attributed to the tsunami and its physical impacts.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] In particular, sessile epibenthic animals and endobenthic animals both decreased in taxon richness.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Mobile epibenthic animals, such as hermit crabs, were not as affected.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] Post-surveys also recorded taxa that were not previously recorded before, suggesting that tsunamis have the potential to introduce species and change taxon composition and local community structure.
[src:american-humane-society/2011-tōhoku-earthquake-and-tsunami-p03] The long term ecological impacts at Sendai Bay and the greater east coast of Japan require further study.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A **501(c)(3) organization** is a United States corporation, trust, unincorporated association, or other type of organization exempt from federal income tax under section 501(c)(3) of Title 26 of the United States Code.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] It is one of the 29 types of 501(c) nonprofit organizations in the U.S.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption applies also for any non-incorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association or foundation organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as *Friends of* organizations.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170 provides a deduction for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Regulations specify which such deductions must be verifiable to be allowed (e.g., receipts for donations of $250 or more).
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The basic requirement of obtaining tax-exempt status is that the organization is specifically limited in powers to purposes that the IRS classifies as tax-exempt purposes.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] This limiting of the powers is crucial to obtaining tax exempt status with the IRS and then on the state level.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Organizations acquire 501(c)(3) tax exemption by filing IRS Form 1023.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] As of 2006, the form must be accompanied by an $850 filing fee if the yearly gross receipts for the organization are expected to average $10,000 or more.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] If yearly gross receipts are expected to average less than $10,000, the filing fee is reduced to $400.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The IRS released a software tool called Cyber Assistant in 2013, which was succeeded by Form 1023-EZ in 2014.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] There is an alternative way for an organization to obtain status if an organization has applied for a determination and either there is an actual controversy regarding a determination or the Internal Revenue Service has failed to make a determination.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Prior to December 30, 1969, nonprofit organizations could declare themselves to be tax-exempt under Section 501(c)(3) without first obtaining Internal Revenue Service recognition by filing Form 1023 and receiving a determination letter.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A nonprofit organization that did so prior to that date could still be subject to challenge of its status by the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] An individual may not take a tax deduction on gifts made to a 501(c)(3) organization that is organized and operated exclusively for the testing for public safety.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] In the case of tuition fees paid to a private 501(c)(3) school or a church school, the payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions because they are payments for services rendered to the payee or the payee's children.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The payments are not tax-deductible charitable contributions even if a significant portion of a church school's curriculum is religious education.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] For a payment to be a tax-deductible charitable contribution, it must be a voluntary transfer of money or other property with no expectation of procuring financial benefit equal to the transfer amount.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Before donating to a 501(c)(3) organization, a donor can consult the searchable online IRS list of charitable organizations to verify that the organization qualifies to receive tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Consumers may file IRS Form 13909, with documentation, to complain about inappropriate or fraudulent (i.e., fundraising, political campaigning, lobbying) activities by any 501(c)(3) organization.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Most 501(c)(3) must disclose the names and addresses of certain large donors to the Internal Revenue Service on their annual returns, but this information is not required to be made available to the public, unless the organization is an independent foundation.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Churches are generally exempt from this reporting requirement.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Every 501(c)(3) organization must make available for public inspection its application for tax-exemption, including its Form 1023 or Form 1023-EZ and any attachments, supporting documents, and follow-up correspondence with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Annual returns must be publicly available for a three-year period beginning with the due date of the return, including any extension of time for filing.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service provides information about specific 501(c)(3) organizations through its Tax Exempt Organization Search online.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A private nonprofit organization, GuideStar, provides information on 501(c)(3) organizations.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] ProPublica's Nonprofit Explorer provides copies of each organization's Form 990 and, for some organizations, audited financial statements.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] WikiCharities, is a nonprofit database of nonprofits and charities by name, location, and topic, that allows each organization to report its financials, leadership, contacts, and other activities.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] However, Open990 was a searchable database of information about organizations that had to shut down due to IRS delays in posting information online.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are prohibited from supporting political candidates, as a result of the Johnson Amendment enacted in 1954.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations are subject to limits on lobbying, having a choice between two sets of rules establishing an upper bound for their lobbying activities.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Section 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of their tax-exempt status if these rules are violated.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] An organization that loses its 501(c)(3) status due to being engaged in political activities cannot subsequently qualify for 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] As a result, it is common for 501(c)(3) organizations to have affiliated nonprofits that are classified as 501(c)(4) organizations, allowing the affiliate to engage in political activity without threatening 501(c)(3) status.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Churches must meet specific requirements to obtain and maintain tax-exempt status; these are outlined in "IRS Publication 1828: Tax Guide for Churches and Religious Organizations".
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] This guide outlines activities allowed and not allowed by churches under the 501(c)(3) designation.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Schools for the preparation of its ministers.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Having an established congregation served by an organized ministry is of central importance.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Points 4, 6, 8, 11, 12, and 13 are also especially important.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Nevertheless, the 14-point list is a guideline; it is not intended to be all-encompassing, and other facts and circumstances may be relevant factors.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Although there is no definitive definition of a church for Internal Revenue Code purposes, in 1986 the United States Tax Court said that "A church is a coherent group of individuals and families that join together to accomplish the religious purposes of mutually held beliefs.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The United States Tax Court has stated that, while a church can certainly broadcast its religious services by radio, radio broadcasts themselves do not constitute a congregation unless there is a group of people physically attending those religious services.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A church can conduct worship services in various specific locations rather than in one official location.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A church may have a significant number of people associate themselves with the church on a regular basis, even if the church does not have a traditional established list of individual members.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] In order to qualify as a tax-exempt church, church activities must be a significant part of the organization's operations.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] An organization whose operations include a substantial nonexempt commercial purposes, such as operating restaurants and grocery stores in a manner consistent with a particular religion's religious beliefs does not qualify as a tax-exempt church.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] In practice, hospital policies often don't cover outside contracted physicians or narrowly defined medically necessary services, leaving patients who technically qualify for charity care still responsible for significant medical bills.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Since section 501(c)(3)'s political-activity prohibition was enacted, "commentators and litigants have challenged the provision on numerous constitutional grounds", such as freedom of speech, vagueness, and equal protection and selective prosecution.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Historically, Supreme Court decisions, such as *Regan v.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Taxation with Representation of Washington*, suggested that the Court, if it were to squarely examine the political-activity prohibition of § 501(c)(3), would uphold it against a constitutional challenge.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] However, some have suggested that a successful challenge to the political activities prohibition of Section 501(c)(3) might be more plausible in light of *Citizens United v.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] In contrast to the prohibition on political campaign interventions by all section 501(c)(3) organizations, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Although the law states that "no substantial part" of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities with large budgets may lawfully expend a million dollars (under the "expenditure" test) or more (under the "substantial part" test) per year on lobbying.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The Internal Revenue Service has never defined the term "substantial part" with respect to lobbying.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] To establish a safe harbor for the "substantial part" test, the United States Congress enacted §501(h), called the Conable election after its author, Representative Barber Conable.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The section establishes limits based on operating budget that a charity can use to determine if it meets the substantial test.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] This changes the prohibition against direct intervention in partisan contests only for lobbying.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The organization is now presumed in compliance with the substantiality test if they work within the limits.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The Conable election requires a charity to file a declaration with the IRS and file a functional distribution of funds spreadsheet with their Form 990.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] IRS form 5768 is required to make the Conable election.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to award grants to foreign charitable organizations if the grants are intended for charitable purposes and the grant funds are subject to the 501(c)(3) organization's control.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Additional procedures are required of 501(c)(3) organizations that are private foundations.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The 501(c)(3) organization's management should review the grant application from the foreign organization, decide whether to award the grant based on the intended use of the funds, and require continuous oversight based on the use of funds.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] If the donor imposes a restriction or earmark that the contribution must be used for foreign activities, then the contribution is deemed to be for the foreign organization rather than the 501(c)(3) organization, and the contribution is not tax-deductible.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] The purpose of the grant to the foreign organization cannot include endorsing or opposing political candidates for elected office in any country.
[src:american-humane-society/501-c-3-organization] If a 501(c)(3) organization sets up and controls a foreign subsidiary to facilitate charitable work in a foreign country, then donors' contributions to the 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible even if intended to fund the foreign charitable activities.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] The film is a co-production between Amblin Entertainment, Reliance Entertainment, Walden Media, and Pariah Entertainment Group.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] It was released by Universal Pictures on January 27, 2017, and grossed $205 million worldwide, and received mixed reviews from critics.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] It was Peggy Lipton's final film role before her death in 2019.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] A sequel, titled *A Dog's Journey*, was released on May 17, 2019.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In the 1950s, a feral puppy wonders about life's true purpose.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Weeks later, he is caught by dog catchers, taken to the pound, and euthanized.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] The dog is reborn as a Red Retriever in 1961.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Leaving his cage at a puppy mill, he is taken by two garbage men who plan to sell him.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Left locked inside their pick-up truck, he begins to die of heatstroke, but is rescued by a mother and her eight-year-old son Ethan Montgomery.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] They break the truck's window and bring him home, naming him Bailey.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey and Ethan bond quickly, especially over the summer at Ethan's grandparents' farm, and Bailey decides Ethan alone is his purpose.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Years pass, and after several attempts at advancing in his job fail, Ethan's father has become an alcoholic.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In 1969, Ethan meets Hannah at a fair with Bailey, and they soon begin dating.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] They spend their summer together through senior year.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] They plan to go to the same college, Ethan getting a football scholarship and Hannah with an academic one.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] At home one night, Ethan's drunken father becomes abusive towards his mother and him.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Ethan orders him to leave and never return, which he does.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Later in 1971 at a football game watched by scouts, Ethan is offered a full scholarship to Michigan State.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] That night, his vindictive classmate Todd throws a lit firecracker into Ethan's house, causing a house fire.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey alerts Ethan, who saves his mother out through an upstairs window.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] However, he loses his rope and has to jump, fracturing his leg.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey attacks Todd, who is arrested by the police when firecrackers fall out of his pocket.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] With his athletic scholarship canceled, Ethan has to go to an agricultural school, where he will learn to take over the farm.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Depressed, Ethan breaks up with Hannah before leaving for college, while Bailey stays with Ethan's maternal grandparents.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey ages and Ethan comes to say goodbye as he dies.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey is reborn as a female German Shepherd puppy, growing into a police dog named Ellie, in the late 1970s/early 1980s, while fully retaining memories of her past lives.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Ellie is partnered with officer Carlos Ruiz, who has recently split up with his partner of the Chicago Police Department and works hard at "seeking" and "finding", now seeing the job as life's purpose.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] They form a close bond, ending after Ellie saves a girl, kidnapped by her mother's ex-boyfriend, from drowning and is then fatally shot by the kidnapper while protecting Carlos.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Reborn in the mid-1980s as a male Corgi, Bailey is adopted by Atlanta college student Maya, who names him Tino.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] She meets Al, a classmate, after Tino falls for Al's dog, a female Landseer named Roxy.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Tino is heartbroken when one day Roxy does not return from the vet.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] As a now elderly Tino dies, he thanks Maya for giving him one of his best lives.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey reincarnates again, this time as a St.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bernard/Australian Shepherd mix puppy in 2014.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] At first adopted by Wendi, he is named Waffles.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Wendi's husband neglects him, refuses to let her keep him inside, and after several years, abandons him.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Waffles searches for a new life, gradually returning to where he spent summers as Bailey.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] He reunites with his old master Ethan, now in his 60s, living on his grandparents' old farm.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Not recognizing him, Ethan takes him to the local animal shelter, but later reclaims him, naming him Buddy.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Finally sensing that he has finally found his true purpose, he reunites Ethan with a widowed Hannah, and they get married.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Buddy shows Ethan that he is his beloved childhood dog, by performing tricks and responding to phrases that were known only to the two of them many years back, such as "boss dog".
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Ethan finds Bailey's collar, now old and rusty, and places it back on Bailey's neck, and they resume playing exactly the way they did years ago.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Bailey narrates that life is about having fun, saving others, finding someone to be with, not getting upset over the past or the future, and living for today.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In 2015, DreamWorks acquired the film rights for Cameron's novel.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On May 8, 2015, it was announced Lasse Hallström would direct the film.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On August 5, 2015, Britt Robertson and Dennis Quaid joined the cast.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On September 18, 2015, Pooch Hall was cast in the film.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On October 15, 2015, Bradley Cooper joined the cast to play Bailey's inner voice, but the role was eventually performed by Josh Gad.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Principal photography began on August 17, 2015.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] During production, controversy ensued over treatment of a dog during filming.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In December 2015, the film switched from a DreamWorks Pictures release to under the Amblin Entertainment banner as per Amblin Partners' newly enacted branded strategy.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] The film was released by Universal Pictures on January 27, 2017.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Universal also distributed it overseas, except for countries where Mister Smith Entertainment handled international sales.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In North America, it was released alongside *Resident Evil: The Final Chapter* and *Gold*, and was projected to gross $18–22 million from 3,050 theaters in its opening weekend, slightly lower than initial $27 million tracking had the film debuting to before boycotts against the film were called for.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] It made $466,000 from Thursday-night previews and $5.3 million on its first day.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] It ended up debuting to $18.2 million, finishing second at the box office behind the second weekend of Universal's own *Split*.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] The film dropped 40.6% in its second weekend, grossing $10.8 million and finishing third at the box office.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On Rotten Tomatoes, the film has an approval rating of 35% based on reviews from 147 critics, with an average rating of 4.9/10.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Audiences polled by CinemaScore gave the film an average grade of "A" on an A+ to F scale.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On January 18, 2017, a video surfaced on TMZ showing footage taken from the set of the film, which shows a male German Shepherd named Hercules being dragged and dipped into rushing water while visibly resisting.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] After a cut in the video, the next clip shows the dog being submerged in the water at the other end of the tank while a voice on set can be heard shouting "Cut it!", and various people are then seen rushing towards the dog.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] The American Humane Association, which ensures that animals are not harmed in entertainment productions, announced that its representative on set had been suspended over the incident, and that the incident was under further investigation.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Actor Josh Gad, who voices the dog in the movie and was not on set during the making of the film, said he was "shaken and sad to see any animal put in a situation against its will".
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Director Lasse Hallström said via Twitter that he "did not witness" the actions in the video, and was "very disturbed" by the footage.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] Due to the release of the video, Universal Pictures cancelled the film's scheduled January 19 Los Angeles premiere.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On June 21, 2017, CEO of Amblin Entertainment Michael Wright announced that a sequel was in development.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] On August 26, 2018, Universal began production on the sequel, which is directed by Gail Mancuso, and was released on May 17, 2019.
[src:american-humane-society/a-dog-s-purpose-film] In addition to Quaid and Gad reprising their roles, the cast also includes Marg Helgenberger (replacing Peggy Lipton, who had become seriously ill), Betty Gilpin, Kathryn Prescott, and Henry Lau.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The book was reviewed in contemporary periodicals including the *London Medical Gazette*, *The Athenaeum*, and *The Veterinary Record*.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] It was later noted by writers including Henry S.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Ralph Fletcher (1780—1851) was a surgeon based in Gloucester.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He studied at St Bartholomew's Hospital in London and received an M.D. from the University of Edinburgh Medical School.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He held appointments at the Gloucester Infirmary, Dispensary, and Lunatic Asylum.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He published medical papers on the relation between mental and physical health.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher was twice elected Mayor of Gloucester and served as president of the local branch of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He lived on Barton Street, near the city's animal pound, and his observations of the animals kept there were said to have inspired *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals*.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In a brief "Preliminary Note", Fletcher writes about the suffering of animals, especially those dependent on humans.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He rejects the view that animals are insensible to pain or that their suffering is divinely ordained, and argues for compassion on moral and theological grounds.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In "Importance of the Subject", Fletcher draws on his experience as president of the Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals in Gloucester.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes that public acts of cruelty form only a small part of a wider problem, and that abuse often takes place in private spaces such as stables, slaughterhouses, and homes.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He argues that existing legislation was inadequate, because small fines and judicial discretion to reduce sentences did not deter offenders.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The main part of the book consists of notes on individual animals and practices.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher describes donkeys as animals commonly subjected to overwork and neglect.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He condemns blood sports such as shooting tied cocks and badger-baiting.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] His discussion of cats and dogs contrasts their treatment: he writes that cats were often tormented or killed for amusement, while dogs suffered from starvation, beatings, cart-work, and fighting.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher criticises methods used in the rearing and slaughter of calves and lambs, including starvation and repeated bleeding to produce white veal.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] He writes about overwork, neglect, and abandonment, and argues that owners as well as drivers should be held legally responsible.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Fletcher ends by calling for tougher penalties for cruelty, official oversight of slaughterhouses and stables, wider public instruction in humane treatment, and hospitals for sick and injured animals.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] A review in the *London Medical Gazette* described the book as the work of a hospital surgeon acquainted with suffering.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] The reviewer agreed with Fletcher's criticism of animal experimentation, but called his proposal for hospitals for animals a "somewhat Utopian scheme" said to have some precedent in the East.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Salt in the "Bibliography of Animal Rights" section of his 1892 work *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress*, where he referred to it as a treatise on animal cruelty.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] In his 1989 reference work *Keyguide to Information Sources in Animal Rights*, Charles R.
[src:american-humane-society/a-few-notes-on-cruelty-to-animals] Magel described *A Few Notes on Cruelty to Animals* as an early account of animal abuse in the Gloucester area and noted its proposal for hospitals for animals modelled on human institutions.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The program has been anchored at various times by a number of other presenters since its debut in 1948.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] It also has used various titles, including *ABC Evening News* from 1968 to 1978, *World News Tonight* from 1978 to 2006, *World News* from 2006 to 2009, and *ABC World News* from 2009 to 2014.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Since 2014, the program has been called *ABC World News Tonight.* The weeknight edition of *ABC World News Tonight* airs live at 6:30 p.m. in the Eastern and 5:30 p.m. in the Central Time Zones.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] However ABC affiliates KGNS, KNOE-2, WEEK-2, and WNCF air *ABC World News Tonight* half-an-hour later on delay.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] WSB also airs it on a delay, the only ABC station in the Eastern Time Zone to do so.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The then-newly-launched ABC television network began a nightly newscast in the summer of 1948, when H.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Baukhage and Jim Gibbons hosted *News and Views*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] This was succeeded by *After the Deadlines* in 1951 and *All Star News* in 1952.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In the fall of 1953, John Daly began anchoring the then-15-minute *John Daly and the News*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Daly, who served as host of the CBS game show *What's My Line?* contemporaneously, anchored the newscast until 1960, with multiple hosts and formats succeeding him.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Anchors of the program during the early 1960s, sometimes for short periods, included Alex Dreier, John Secondari, Fendall Winston Yerxa, Al Mann, Bill Shadel, and the three-person team of John Cameron Swayze (formerly of NBC), Bill Lawrence, and Bill Sheehan.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In 1962, Ron Cochran was appointed as full-time anchor, staying with the program, entitled, “Ron Cochran with the News”, until 1965.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] After Cochran left the program, Peter Jennings, a Canadian journalist who was 26 years old at the time, was named anchor of the retitled *Peter Jennings with the News*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In December 1967, the inexperienced Jennings left the anchor chair and was reassigned by the news division as an international correspondent for the news program.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The newly renamed *ABC Evening News* was hosted, in succession, by Bob Young (January 1968 to May 1968), and then by Frank Reynolds (May 1968 to December 1970), who was joined by Howard K.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The program expanded from 15 to 30 minutes in January 1967, nearly 3+1⁄2 years after both CBS and NBC had expanded their evening news programs to a half-hour.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Harry Reasoner, formerly of CBS News and *60 Minutes*, joined ABC News in 1970 to co-anchor *ABC Evening News* with Smith, beginning that December, replacing Reynolds.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The ratings increased steadily, but still remained in third place, behind dominant CBS and NBC.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Smith was moved to a commentator role, and Reasoner briefly assumed sole-anchor responsibilities until he was paired with Barbara Walters, who became the first female network anchor when she joined the program on October 4, 1976.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Ratings for the nightly news broadcast declined shortly thereafter, possibly due in part to the lack of chemistry between Reasoner and Walters.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Reasoner would eventually return to CBS and *60 Minutes*, while Walters became a regular on the newsmagazine *20/20*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Starting in 1973, before the advent of closed captioning, PBS began airing an open captioned version of the *ABC Evening News* that was distributed to various public television stations throughout the U.S., airing mostly in late-night timeslots five hours after the original ABC broadcast.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] It was originally titled *The Captioned ABC Evening News*, and later as *The Captioned ABC News*, and it was originally distributed by the Eastern Educational Network, before becoming a national program under PBS a year later.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The practice continued until 1982, when real-time closed captioning was first introduced in the United States by the National Captioning Institute.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Always the perennial third in the national ratings, ABC News president Roone Arledge reformatted the program, relaunching it as *World News Tonight* in July 1978.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Reynolds, who was demoted when the network hired Reasoner, returned as lead anchor, reporting from ABC News' Washington, D.C. bureau.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Max Robinson – who became the first African American network news anchor upon his appointment on the program – anchored national news from the news division's Chicago bureau.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Peter Jennings, who also returned for a second stint, reported international headlines from the division's London bureau.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Occasional contributions included special reports by Walters, who was credited as anchor of the special coverage desk from New York City and worldwide, and commentary by Smith, who was easing into eventual retirement.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The program's distinct and easily identifiable theme (whose four-note musical signature was eventually used on other ABC News programs) was written by Bob Israel.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Ratings slowly climbed to the point where *World News Tonight* eventually beat both *NBC Nightly News* and the *CBS Evening News*, marking the first time ever that ABC had the most-watched network evening newscast.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In April 1983, Reynolds became ill, and ABC News brought in *This Week* moderator David Brinkley to fill in for Reynolds.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] This arrangement continued until July 4; when ABC news summoned Peter Jennings to leave London and anchor from Washington, leaving both him and Robinson to co-anchor the broadcast until Reynolds' planned return.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] However, Reynolds died on July 20, 1983, from bone cancer.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] A rotation of anchors hosted the program until August 9, 1983, when ABC announced that Jennings became the sole anchor and senior editor of *World News Tonight*, which took effect September 5, and on that day, the program began broadcasting from New York City on a regular basis.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Bill Owen would replace Bill Rice as announcer for a year.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In September 1984, the program was renamed *World News Tonight with Peter Jennings* to reflect its sole anchor and senior editor.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Robinson left ABC News earlier in 1984, after stints of anchoring news briefs and the weekend editions of *World News Tonight*; he died from complications of AIDS in 1988.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] With Jennings as lead anchor, *World News Tonight* was the most-watched national newscast from February 27, 1989, to November 1, 1996, but from then on until February 2007, it placed second behind its main rival, *NBC Nightly News*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In April 2005, Jennings announced that he had been diagnosed with lung cancer and, as before, other ABC News anchors, including *20/20* co-anchor Elizabeth Vargas and *Good Morning America* co-anchor Charles Gibson, filled in for him.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Jennings died of lung cancer on August 7, 2005, at his apartment in New York City, at age 67.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The August 8, 2005, edition of the program was dedicated in memory of Jennings and looked back at his four-decade career in news.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] His death ended the era of the so-called "Big Three" anchors: Jennings, NBC's Tom Brokaw, and CBS's Dan Rather (the latter two had retired from their positions as the respective anchors of *NBC Nightly News* and the *CBS Evening News* within the year prior to Jennings's death).
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] During his career, Jennings had reported from every major world capital and war zone, and from all 50 U.S. states, according to the network.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Jennings was known for his ability to calmly portray events as they were happening and for his coverage of many major world events such as the September 11 attacks and the dawn of the new millennium.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] As a tribute to its recently deceased anchor, ABC continued to introduce the broadcast as *World News Tonight with Peter Jennings* in the week following his death.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Gibson anchored the broadcast the first part of the week, playing a slow arrangement of the traditional theme music in memory of Jennings; Bob Woodruff anchored the final edition of *World News Tonight with Peter Jennings* on August 12, 2005.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] That night's broadcast ended with one of Jennings's favorite pieces of music instead of the traditional theme music.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Beginning on August 15, 2005, the broadcast was introduced simply as *World News Tonight* and it remained that way until January 2006.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The program would return to a two-anchor format, when in early December 2005, ABC News announced that Elizabeth Vargas and Bob Woodruff would be the new permanent co-anchors of *World News Tonight*, replacing Jennings.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] People in the news industry looked at the choice of Vargas and Woodruff by ABC News as the start of a new era in network television news.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The broadcast was produced live three times per day – the regular live broadcast for the Eastern and Central Time Zones, plus separate broadcasts for the Mountain and Pacific Time Zones.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In addition, a live webcast, *World News Now* (which, incidentally, carried the same title as ABC's overnight news program), with a newsbrief and a preview of that evening's broadcast, was launched.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Eastern Time on ABC News Now and ABCNews.com, and could be viewed throughout the rest of the day after 4:00 pm.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] On January 29, 2006, Woodruff and his cameraman, Doug Vogt, were injured by a road-side bomb while riding in an Iraqi military convoy.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Both underwent surgery at a U.S. military hospital in Balad, Iraq (50 miles (80 km) north of Baghdad).
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Both men incurred head injuries in the incident, even though they were both wearing body armor and helmets.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Woodruff and Vogt were then evacuated to a U.S. military hospital in Germany, before later being transferred to Bethesda Naval Hospital in Maryland for further treatment and released for outpatient treatment.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Within a few months after Woodruff's accident, ABC News announced that Vargas was pregnant and due to give birth to her second child in late summer.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] For about a month, *Good Morning America* co-hosts Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer had alternated co-anchoring the newscast with Vargas.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] During the spring of 2006, Vargas mostly anchored the broadcast alone, becoming the first *de facto* solo female evening news anchor.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] At the time, it was unknown what ABC News planned to do until Woodruff returned to the anchor chair, which appeared not to be within the near future, and when Vargas began her maternity leave.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Rumors flew that Sawyer wanted to become the sole anchor of *World News Tonight* to beat Katie Couric's switch to the anchor chair at the *CBS Evening News*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] However, *New York Post* columnist Cindy Adams reported that Gibson would become Woodruff's "temporary permanent replacement".
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Also starting in early 2006, the West Coast editions of *World News Tonight* were scaled back because Vargas anchored the broadcast on her own at the time.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In May 2006, Vargas announced her resignation from *World News Tonight*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Charles Gibson was then named sole anchor of the program, effectively replacing Vargas and her injured co-anchor Woodruff.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Vargas cited her doctors' recommendation to cut back her schedule considerably because of her maternity leave, and her wish to spend more time with her new baby.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] She has since returned to co-anchor *20/20* and ABC News specials, and has served as a substitute anchor on *World News Tonight* under Gibson and his successors.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Woodruff, although still recovering from his injuries, returned to *World News Tonight* as a correspondent on February 28, 2007.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Indeed, the advertising campaign focused on Gibson's experience, calling him "Your Trusted Source", similar to a campaign for Jennings, "Trust Is Earned", in the wake of the Killian documents controversy at CBS and Brian Williams's assumption of the NBC anchor chair.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] On July 19, 2006, ABC News announced that *World News Tonight* would have its name officially changed to *World News with Charles Gibson*.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] The network chose to make the, albeit minor, change to remove "Tonight" from the title to reflect the program's expansion into the "24-hour space created by the digital world".
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] In the February 2007 sweeps, *World News with Charles Gibson* achieved the number-one spot in the Nielsen ratings among the network evening news broadcasts, overtaking *NBC Nightly News*, marking ABC News' first victory since the week Jennings died in August 2005.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] On August 25, 2008, *World News* became the fourth and final network evening newscast to begin broadcasting in HD.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] On September 2, 2009, ABC News announced that Gibson would retire from ABC News altogether on December 18, 2009, and that Sawyer would assume the anchor desk on December 21, 2009.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Gibson's final broadcast ended with a video tribute that included all of the living former U.S.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Presidents, former ABC anchors, actors and actresses, singers, comedians, Mickey Mouse, Kermit the Frog, athletes, the commander of the International Space Station, competitors Couric and Williams, and was capped off by U.S.
[src:american-humane-society/abc-world-news-tonight] Long-time ABC journalist and anchorwoman Diane Sawyer (who previously co-anchored *Good Morning America* with predecessor Gibson) began anchoring the broadcast, which amended its title to *ABC World News*, on December 21, 2009.
